{"title_page": "Lake Ontario Waterkeeper", "text_new": "{{Infobox Organization\n|name         = Lake Ontario Waterkeeper\n|formation    = 2001\n|type         = Environmental justice advocacy\n|headquarters = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n|language     = [[English language|English]]\n|leader_title = President\n|leader_name  = Mark Mattson\n|key_people   = Krystyn Tully\n|website      = http://waterkeeper.ca\n}}\n'''Lake Ontario Waterkeeper''' is a [[Toronto]]-based [[environmental justice]] [[advocacy group]] founded in 2001, with [[Lake Ontario]], the [[Great Lakes Basin]], and allied waterways at heart.  It is a licensed member of the [[New York City|New York]]-based [[Waterkeeper Alliance]],<ref name=WALOW>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterkeeper.org/subsites/subcontact.aspx?userid=82 |accessdate=2009-02-12 |title=Waterkeeper: Lake Ontario Waterkeeper: Contact Us |publisher=[[Waterkeeper Alliance]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713070203/http://www.waterkeeper.org/subsites/subcontact.aspx?userid=82 |archivedate=July 13, 2007 }}</ref> and a registered Canadian charity.<ref name=CRALOW>\n{{cite web\n|url= http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/ebci/haip/srch/sec/SrchInput03Render-e?bn=862622750RR0001\n|title= Canadian Registered Charities - Detail page\n|accessdate= 2009-02-12\n|publisher= [[Canada Revenue Agency]]\n}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> It is led by President Mark Mattson, an environmental lawyer, and Vice President Krystyn Tully.<ref name=\"eye-pp\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_05.22.03/news/beaches.php \n |accessdate=2007-10-23 \n |title=Political pollution \n |publisher=[[Eye Weekly]] \n |date=May 22, 2003 \n |first=Edward \n |last=Keenan \n |author2=Prittie, Jennifier \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522151643/http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_05.22.03/news/beaches.php \n |archivedate=May 22, 2011 \n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |title=From Chicago to Toronto, cities spilling waste into Great Lakes \n |publisher=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel \n |date=June 26, 2004 \n |url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=239659&format=print \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601234149/http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=239659 \n |archivedate=June 1, 2008 \n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |title=Ships sweep toxic trash into our lake \u2013 and feds just let it happen \n |publisher=Now Toronto \n |date=May 19, 2005 \n |url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2005-05-19/news_story.php \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070419212453/http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2005-05-19/news_story.php \n |archivedate=April 19, 2007 \n}}</ref>\n\n==Actions and initiatives==\nIn Summer of 2001 LOW triggered a $250 Million Federal Government remediation plan at [[Port Granby]] near [[Port Hope, Ontario]]. The dump, was established by [[Eldorado Mining and Refining Limited]] (and now managed by [[Cameco Corp.]]).<ref name=Yachting>\n{{cite journal | last = McCutcheon  | first = Duff  | title = Mark Mattson, Lake Ontario Keeper  | journal = [[Canadian Yachting]]\n| pages = 26, 27  | publisher = Kerrwil Publications Limited, Oct 2002  | date = October 1, 2007  | id = 347122521{{ProQuest|222821010}}  | issn = 0384-0999  }}</ref> In 2005 LOW campaigned the City of [[Kingston, Ontario]] to disclose timely data about repeated sewage discharges into Lake Ontario.<ref>Kingston Whig-Standard (ON) - Final - 23 December 2005</ref> In 2006 LOW produced \"Heart of A Lake\" concert tour to several cities in [[Ontario, Canada]] ''blending activism with art''.<ref>\n{{cite news |publisher = Canada NewsWire |location = Ottawa |date = August 28, 2006 |pages = 1 |title = Gord Downie and Waterkeeper bring \"Heart of A Lake\" to Whitby, Port Hope, Kingston}}</ref> Starting in 2006 LOW started a campaign opposing the burning of tires by Lafarge operations in [[Bath, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher= Kingston Whig-Standard |location = Ontario |date = September 12, 2007 |title = Lafarge review rolls on}}</ref> In 2007 LOW compelled the City of [[Toronto]] to disclose specific reasons why beaches are closed, and used the legal system to force the City to take responsibility.<ref name=\"eye-pp\" /> Citing a \"little-known provincial environmental guideline called F-5 that says municipalities must ensure that beaches are clean enough for swimming 95 per cent of the time.\" This builds on a 2006 LOW report \"Investigating Municipal Beaches: Lessons from Bluffer's Park\" which cited some beaches were closed to swimming 42 per cent of the time.<ref name=\"eye-ctcb\">\n{{cite news|url=http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_06.15.06/city/news.php |title=Calling the City's Bluff: One advocate says Toronto needs to stop making excuses and start cleaning up our beaches |first=Mark |last=Medley |publisher=Eye Weekly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522151650/http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_06.15.06/city/news.php |archivedate=2011-05-22 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the organization launched '''Swim Drink Fish Music''', an online music club which features rare and exclusive tracks by Canadian musicians.<ref>[http://community.hour.ca/blogs/music_news/archive/2010/08/25/great-lake-swimmers-record-quot-ballad-of-a-fisherman-s-wife-quot-for-swim-drink-fish-music-club.aspx \"Great Lake Swimmers Record 'Ballad of a Fisherman's Wife' for Swim Drink Fish Music Club\"]{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Hour (magazine)|Hour]]'', August 25, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Notable supporters==\n*[[The Tragically Hip]] and particularly their frontman [[Gord Downie]]<ref>{{cite news |title= Stars align in Banff |publisher= Calgary Sun |date= January 18, 2007 |url= http://www.calgarysun.com/cgi-bin/publish.cgi?p=169265&x=articles&s=showbiz }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=LiveShows>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterkeeper.ca/content/other/3_live_shows_raise_awareness_c.php |accessdate=2007-10-23 |title=3 live shows raise awareness, cash for Lake Ontario Watershed: Chris Brown, Barenaked Ladies, Sarah Harmer perform this week |author=Lake Ontario Waterkeeper |date=September 25, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028205121/http://www.waterkeeper.ca/content/other/3_live_shows_raise_awareness_c.php |archivedate=2007-10-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Edward Burtynsky]], photographer <ref>{{cite AV media | people=Edward Burtynsky | title=Edward Burtynsky uncut interview for Lake Ontario Waterkeeper | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CQ5u9L3i4Vw }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1152983/lake-ontario-waterkeeper-robert-f-kennedy-jr-and-edward-burtynsky-host-the-second-annual-waterkeeper-gala-on-may-23 | title= Lake Ontario Waterkeeper, Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. and Edward Burtynsky Host the Second Annual Waterkeeper Gala on May 23 |accessdate=2013-04-25 }}</ref>\n*[[Sarah Harmer]], folk musician<ref name=LiveShows /><ref name=\"ca\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/44503/sarah-harmer-gord-downie-and-others-team-up-in-support-of-lake-ontario-waterkeeper \n |title=Sarah Harmer, Gord Downie And Others Team Up In Support Of Lake Ontario Waterkeeper \n |accessdate=2009-03-14 \n |first=Moya \n |last=Dillon \n |publisher=[[Chart (magazine)|ChartAttack]] \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607131336/http://www.chartattack.com/news/44503/sarah-harmer-gord-downie-and-others-team-up-in-support-of-lake-ontario-waterkeeper \n |archivedate=2011-06-07 \n}}</ref>\n*[[David Suzuki]], Canadian environmentalist and broadcaster.<ref name=LiveShows />\n*[[Bruce Cockburn]], musician<ref name=LiveShows />\n*[[Chris Brown (Canadian singer)|Chris Brown]], musician<ref name=\"ca\" />\n*[[Law Foundation of Ontario]]<ref>{{cite news |publisher= Canada NewsWire |location= Ottawa |date= June 6, 2007 |pages=  1 |title= The Law Foundation of Ontario expands support to public interest organizations}}</ref><ref>[http://www.law.utoronto.ca/documents/press_releases/05_06_LawFoundation.doc The Law Foundation of Ontario Selects Six Public Interest Organizations for Innovative Articling Fellowships]. Press Release. June 16, 2005.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Great Lakes Areas of Concern]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://waterkeeper.ca/ Lake Ontario Waterkeeper website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070703170521/http://www.waterkeepers.ca/local.html List of all local Canadian Waterkeeper organizations]\n\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2001]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Organization\n|name         = Lake Ontario Waterkeeper\n|formation    = 2001\n|type         = Environmental justice advocacy\n|headquarters = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n|language     = [[English language|English]]\n|leader_title = President\n|leader_name  = Mark Mattson\n|key_people   = Krystyn Tully\n|website      = http://waterkeeper.ca\n}}\n'''Lake Ontario Waterkeeper''' is a [[Toronto]]-based environmental justice [[advocacy group]] founded in 2001, with [[Lake Ontario]], the [[Great Lakes Basin]], and allied waterways at heart.  It is a licensed member of the [[New York City|New York]]-based [[Waterkeeper Alliance]],<ref name=WALOW>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterkeeper.org/subsites/subcontact.aspx?userid=82 |accessdate=2009-02-12 |title=Waterkeeper: Lake Ontario Waterkeeper: Contact Us |publisher=[[Waterkeeper Alliance]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713070203/http://www.waterkeeper.org/subsites/subcontact.aspx?userid=82 |archivedate=July 13, 2007 }}</ref> and a registered Canadian charity.<ref name=CRALOW>\n{{cite web\n|url= http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/ebci/haip/srch/sec/SrchInput03Render-e?bn=862622750RR0001\n|title= Canadian Registered Charities - Detail page\n|accessdate= 2009-02-12\n|publisher= [[Canada Revenue Agency]]\n}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> It is led by President Mark Mattson, an environmental lawyer, and Vice President Krystyn Tully.<ref name=\"eye-pp\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_05.22.03/news/beaches.php \n |accessdate=2007-10-23 \n |title=Political pollution \n |publisher=[[Eye Weekly]] \n |date=May 22, 2003 \n |first=Edward \n |last=Keenan \n |author2=Prittie, Jennifier \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522151643/http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_05.22.03/news/beaches.php \n |archivedate=May 22, 2011 \n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |title=From Chicago to Toronto, cities spilling waste into Great Lakes \n |publisher=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel \n |date=June 26, 2004 \n |url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=239659&format=print \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601234149/http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=239659 \n |archivedate=June 1, 2008 \n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |title=Ships sweep toxic trash into our lake \u2013 and feds just let it happen \n |publisher=Now Toronto \n |date=May 19, 2005 \n |url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2005-05-19/news_story.php \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070419212453/http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2005-05-19/news_story.php \n |archivedate=April 19, 2007 \n}}</ref>\n\n==Actions and initiatives==\nIn Summer of 2001 LOW triggered a $250 Million Federal Government remediation plan at [[Port Granby]] near [[Port Hope, Ontario]]. The dump, was established by [[Eldorado Mining and Refining Limited]] (and now managed by [[Cameco Corp.]]).<ref name=Yachting>\n{{cite journal | last = McCutcheon  | first = Duff  | title = Mark Mattson, Lake Ontario Keeper  | journal = [[Canadian Yachting]]\n| pages = 26, 27  | publisher = Kerrwil Publications Limited, Oct 2002  | date = October 1, 2007  | id = 347122521{{ProQuest|222821010}}  | issn = 0384-0999  }}</ref> In 2005 LOW campaigned the City of [[Kingston, Ontario]] to disclose timely data about repeated sewage discharges into Lake Ontario.<ref>Kingston Whig-Standard (ON) - Final - 23 December 2005</ref> In 2006 LOW produced \"Heart of A Lake\" concert tour to several cities in [[Ontario, Canada]] ''blending activism with art''.<ref>\n{{cite news |publisher = Canada NewsWire |location = Ottawa |date = August 28, 2006 |pages = 1 |title = Gord Downie and Waterkeeper bring \"Heart of A Lake\" to Whitby, Port Hope, Kingston}}</ref> Starting in 2006 LOW started a campaign opposing the burning of tires by Lafarge operations in [[Bath, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher= Kingston Whig-Standard |location = Ontario |date = September 12, 2007 |title = Lafarge review rolls on}}</ref> In 2007 LOW compelled the City of [[Toronto]] to disclose specific reasons why beaches are closed, and used the legal system to force the City to take responsibility.<ref name=\"eye-pp\" /> Citing a \"little-known provincial environmental guideline called F-5 that says municipalities must ensure that beaches are clean enough for swimming 95 per cent of the time.\" This builds on a 2006 LOW report \"Investigating Municipal Beaches: Lessons from Bluffer's Park\" which cited some beaches were closed to swimming 42 per cent of the time.<ref name=\"eye-ctcb\">\n{{cite news|url=http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_06.15.06/city/news.php |title=Calling the City's Bluff: One advocate says Toronto needs to stop making excuses and start cleaning up our beaches |first=Mark |last=Medley |publisher=Eye Weekly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522151650/http://www.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_06.15.06/city/news.php |archivedate=2011-05-22 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the organization launched '''Swim Drink Fish Music''', an online music club which features rare and exclusive tracks by Canadian musicians.<ref>[http://community.hour.ca/blogs/music_news/archive/2010/08/25/great-lake-swimmers-record-quot-ballad-of-a-fisherman-s-wife-quot-for-swim-drink-fish-music-club.aspx \"Great Lake Swimmers Record 'Ballad of a Fisherman's Wife' for Swim Drink Fish Music Club\"]{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Hour (magazine)|Hour]]'', August 25, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Notable supporters==\n*[[The Tragically Hip]] and particularly their frontman [[Gord Downie]]<ref>{{cite news |title= Stars align in Banff |publisher= Calgary Sun |date= January 18, 2007 |url= http://www.calgarysun.com/cgi-bin/publish.cgi?p=169265&x=articles&s=showbiz }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=LiveShows>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterkeeper.ca/content/other/3_live_shows_raise_awareness_c.php |accessdate=2007-10-23 |title=3 live shows raise awareness, cash for Lake Ontario Watershed: Chris Brown, Barenaked Ladies, Sarah Harmer perform this week |author=Lake Ontario Waterkeeper |date=September 25, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028205121/http://www.waterkeeper.ca/content/other/3_live_shows_raise_awareness_c.php |archivedate=2007-10-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Edward Burtynsky]], photographer <ref>{{cite AV media | people=Edward Burtynsky | title=Edward Burtynsky uncut interview for Lake Ontario Waterkeeper | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CQ5u9L3i4Vw }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1152983/lake-ontario-waterkeeper-robert-f-kennedy-jr-and-edward-burtynsky-host-the-second-annual-waterkeeper-gala-on-may-23 | title= Lake Ontario Waterkeeper, Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. and Edward Burtynsky Host the Second Annual Waterkeeper Gala on May 23 |accessdate=2013-04-25 }}</ref>\n*[[Sarah Harmer]], folk musician<ref name=LiveShows /><ref name=\"ca\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/44503/sarah-harmer-gord-downie-and-others-team-up-in-support-of-lake-ontario-waterkeeper \n |title=Sarah Harmer, Gord Downie And Others Team Up In Support Of Lake Ontario Waterkeeper \n |accessdate=2009-03-14 \n |first=Moya \n |last=Dillon \n |publisher=[[Chart (magazine)|ChartAttack]] \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607131336/http://www.chartattack.com/news/44503/sarah-harmer-gord-downie-and-others-team-up-in-support-of-lake-ontario-waterkeeper \n |archivedate=2011-06-07 \n}}</ref>\n*[[David Suzuki]], Canadian environmentalist and broadcaster.<ref name=LiveShows />\n*[[Bruce Cockburn]], musician<ref name=LiveShows />\n*[[Chris Brown (Canadian singer)|Chris Brown]], musician<ref name=\"ca\" />\n*[[Law Foundation of Ontario]]<ref>{{cite news |publisher= Canada NewsWire |location= Ottawa |date= June 6, 2007 |pages=  1 |title= The Law Foundation of Ontario expands support to public interest organizations}}</ref><ref>[http://www.law.utoronto.ca/documents/press_releases/05_06_LawFoundation.doc The Law Foundation of Ontario Selects Six Public Interest Organizations for Innovative Articling Fellowships]. Press Release. June 16, 2005.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Great Lakes Areas of Concern]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://waterkeeper.ca/ Lake Ontario Waterkeeper website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070703170521/http://www.waterkeepers.ca/local.html List of all local Canadian Waterkeeper organizations]\n\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2001]]\n", "name_user": "Daask", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkEnvironmental justiceusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Ontario_Waterkeeper"}
{"title_page": "Juan Pablo Ruiz P\u00e9rez", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=June 2015}}\n{{spanish name|first=Ruiz|second=P\u00e9rez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Juan Pablo\n| image = \n| fullname = Juan Pablo Ruiz P\u00e9rez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|11|5|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[La Puebla del R\u00edo]], [[Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.90}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|Centre forward]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Real Betis|Betis]] \n| years1 = 2001\n| years2 = 2001\n| years3 = 2002\n| years4 = 2002\u20132003\n| years5 = 2003\u20132004\n| years6 = 2004\n| years7 = 2004\u20132005\n| years8 = 2005\u20132006\n| years9 = 2006\u20132008\n| years10 = 2008\u20132009\n| years11 = 2010\n| years12 = 2010\u20132012\n| clubs1 = [[Real Betis B|Betis B]]\n| clubs2 = [[Racing Club Portuense|Portuense]] \n| clubs3 = [[Hell\u00edn Deportivo|Hell\u00edn]]\n| clubs4 = [[Dos Hermanas CF|Dos Hermanas]]\n| clubs5 = [[\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9|\u00c9cija]] \n| clubs6 = [[Lucena CF|Lucentino]] \n| clubs7 = [[CF Sporting Mahon\u00e9s|Sporting Mahon\u00e9s]]\n| clubs8 = [[Algeciras CF|Algeciras]]  \n| clubs9 = [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico|Sevilla B]] \n| clubs10 = [[FC Cartagena|Cartagena]] \n| clubs11 = [[Valencia CF Mestalla|Valencia B]]\n| clubs12 = [[\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9|\u00c9cija]] \n| caps1 = 1\n| caps2 =  \n| caps3 = \n| caps4 = \n| caps5 = 5\n| caps6 = 12\n| caps7 = 38\n| caps8 = 36\n| caps9 = 63\n| caps10 = 31\n| caps11 = 13\n| caps12 = 66\n| totalcaps = 265\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 = \n| goals3 = \n| goals4 = \n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 4\n| goals7 = 23\n| goals8 = 14\n| goals9 = 12\n| goals10 = 9\n| goals11 = 2\n| goals12 = 16\n| totalgoals = 80\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Juan Pablo Ruiz P\u00e9rez''' (born 5 November 1982), known as '''Juan Pablo''', is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre forward]].\n\n==Football career==\nJuan Pablo was born in [[La Puebla del R\u00edo]], [[Province of Seville]]. During his early career, spent mainly in the lower leagues, he \u2013 an unsuccessful [[Real Betis]] youth graduate \u2013 represented [[Real Betis B|Betis B]], [[Racing Club Portuense]], [[Hell\u00edn Deportivo]], [[Dos Hermanas CF]], [[\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9]], [[Lucena CF|Atl\u00e9tico Lucentino]], [[CF Sporting Mahon\u00e9s]], [[Algeciras CF]] and [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico]]. With the latter, he made his [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] debut in the [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2007\u201308 season]], scoring four goals in 30 games as the [[Andalusia]]ns retained their division status in their debut campaign in the competition.<ref>[http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/2a_division/cronica/es/desarrollo/1135218.html El Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico tuvo una gran despedida (Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico closed in style)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 15 June 2008 (in Spanish)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sevillismoenvena.com/2015/11/que-fue-de-los-integrantes-del-sevilla.html|title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 fue de los integrantes del Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico de Segunda divisi\u00f3n?|trans-title=What happened to members of Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico of ''Segunda divisi\u00f3n''?|publisher=Sevillismo en Vena|language=Spanish|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2008, Juan Pablo joined [[FC Cartagena]] of [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]. On 24 May 2009 he netted the deciding goal at [[CD Alcoyano]] ([[2009 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|2\u20132, 4\u20133 aggregate win]]), as the [[Region of Murcia|Murcian]] side \u2013 under their new denomination \u2013 [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|promoted]] to the second level for the first time ever.<ref>[http://www.laverdad.es/alicante/20090525/deportes_alicante/alcoyano/cartagena-asciende-segunda-alcoyano-20090525.html El Cartagena asciende a Segunda y el Alcoyano se la jugar\u00e1 en la repesca (2\u20132) (Cartagena promote to ''Segunda'' and Alcoyano to leave it all for play-offs (2\u20132))]; [[La Verdad (Murcia)|La Verdad]], 25 May 2009 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nAfter initially refusing to renew his link and wanting a buyout, which eventually led to his demotion to reserves Cartagena La Uni\u00f3n (only for training), Juan Pablo finally accepted, and was reinstated by Cartagena in January 2010.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2009/12/29/futbol/equipos/cartagena/1262122527.html Juan Pablo acepta al fin reincorporarse al Cartagena (Juan Pablo finally accepts rejoining Cartagena)]; Marca, 29 December 2009 (in Spanish)</ref> On the 29th, however, he was released, joining [[Valencia CF]]'s [[Valencia CF Mestalla|reserves]] shortly after.<ref>[http://www.valenciacf.com/ver/19430/juan-pablo--nuevo-jugador-del-filial.html Juan Pablo, nuevo jugador del filial (Juan Pablo, new reserve team player)]; Valencia CF, 1 February 2010 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, after [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his last team's relegation]], Juan Pablo continued his career in the third tier, returning to former club \u00c9cija. He retired at the age of only 30 after becoming despondent with the sport, later working as manager and personal driver of [[Bullfighting|bullfighter]] Morante de la Puebla.<ref>[http://www.laverdad.es/murcia/deportes/201504/27/juan-pablo-quiso-heroe-20150427012735-v.html Juan Pablo no quiso ser un h\u00e9roe (Juan Pablo did not want to be a hero)]; La Verdad, 27 April 2015 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|6296|Juan Pablo}}\n*{{Soccerway|juan-pablo-ruiz-perez/62083|Juan Pablo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Juan Pablo Ruiz Perez}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Seville (comarca)]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Andalusian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Betis Deportivo Balompi\u00e9 footballers]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9 players]]\n[[Category:Algeciras CF footballers]]\n[[Category:Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico players]]\n[[Category:FC Cartagena footballers]]\n[[Category:Valencia CF Mestalla footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=June 2015}}\n{{spanish name|first=Ruiz|second=P\u00e9rez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Juan Pablo\n| image = \n| fullname = Juan Pablo Ruiz P\u00e9rez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|11|5|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[La Puebla del R\u00edo]], [[Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.90}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|Centre forward]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Real Betis|Betis]] \n| years1 = 2001\n| years2 = 2001\n| years3 = 2002\n| years4 = 2002\u20132003\n| years5 = 2003\u20132004\n| years6 = 2004\n| years7 = 2004\u20132005\n| years8 = 2005\u20132006\n| years9 = 2006\u20132008\n| years10 = 2008\u20132009\n| years11 = 2010\n| years12 = 2010\u20132012\n| clubs1 = [[Real Betis B|Betis B]]\n| clubs2 = [[Racing Club Portuense|Portuense]] \n| clubs3 = [[Hell\u00edn Deportivo|Hell\u00edn]]\n| clubs4 = [[Dos Hermanas CF|Dos Hermanas]]\n| clubs5 = [[\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9|\u00c9cija]] \n| clubs6 = [[Lucena CF|Lucentino]] \n| clubs7 = [[CF Sporting Mahon\u00e9s|Sporting Mahon\u00e9s]]\n| clubs8 = [[Algeciras CF|Algeciras]]  \n| clubs9 = [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico|Sevilla B]] \n| clubs10 = [[FC Cartagena|Cartagena]] \n| clubs11 = [[Valencia CF Mestalla|Valencia B]]\n| clubs12 = [[\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9|\u00c9cija]] \n| caps1 = 1\n| caps2 =  \n| caps3 = \n| caps4 = \n| caps5 = 5\n| caps6 = 12\n| caps7 = 38\n| caps8 = 36\n| caps9 = 63\n| caps10 = 31\n| caps11 = 13\n| caps12 = 66\n| totalcaps = 265\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 = \n| goals3 = \n| goals4 = \n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 4\n| goals7 = 23\n| goals8 = 14\n| goals9 = 12\n| goals10 = 9\n| goals11 = 2\n| goals12 = 16\n| totalgoals = 80\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Juan Pablo Ruiz P\u00e9rez''' (born 5 November 1982 in [[La Puebla del R\u00edo]], [[Province of Seville|Seville]]), known as '''Juan Pablo''', is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre forward]].\n\n==Football career==\nDuring his early career, spent mainly in the lower leagues, Juan Pablo \u2013 an unsuccessful [[Real Betis]] youth graduate \u2013 represented [[Real Betis B|Betis B]], [[Racing Club Portuense]], [[Hell\u00edn Deportivo]], [[Dos Hermanas CF]], [[\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9]], [[Lucena CF|Atl\u00e9tico Lucentino]], [[CF Sporting Mahon\u00e9s]], [[Algeciras CF]] and [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico]]. With the latter, he made his [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] debut in the [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2007\u201308 season]], scoring four goals in 30 games as the [[Andalusia]]ns retained their division status in their debut campaign in the competition.<ref>[http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/2a_division/cronica/es/desarrollo/1135218.html El Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico tuvo una gran despedida (Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico closed in style)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 15 June 2008 (in Spanish)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sevillismoenvena.com/2015/11/que-fue-de-los-integrantes-del-sevilla.html|title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 fue de los integrantes del Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico de Segunda divisi\u00f3n?|trans-title=What happened to members of Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico of ''Segunda divisi\u00f3n''?|publisher=Sevillismo en Vena|language=Spanish|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2008, Juan Pablo joined [[FC Cartagena]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]. On 24 May 2009 he netted the deciding goal at [[CD Alcoyano]] ([[2009 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|2\u20132, 4\u20133 aggregate win]]), as the [[Region of Murcia|Murcian]] side \u2013 under their new denomination \u2013 [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|promoted]] to the second level for the first time ever.<ref>[http://www.laverdad.es/alicante/20090525/deportes_alicante/alcoyano/cartagena-asciende-segunda-alcoyano-20090525.html El Cartagena asciende a Segunda y el Alcoyano se la jugar\u00e1 en la repesca (2\u20132) (Cartagena promote to ''Segunda'' and Alcoyano to leave it all for play-offs (2\u20132))]; [[La Verdad (Murcia)|La Verdad]], 25 May 2009 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nAfter initially refusing to renew his link and wanting a buyout, which eventually led to his demotion to reserves Cartagena La Uni\u00f3n (only for training), Juan Pablo finally accepted, and was reinstated by Cartagena in January 2010.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2009/12/29/futbol/equipos/cartagena/1262122527.html Juan Pablo acepta al fin reincorporarse al Cartagena (Juan Pablo finally accepts rejoining Cartagena)]; Marca, 29 December 2009 (in Spanish)</ref> On the 29th, however, he was released, joining [[Valencia CF]]'s [[Valencia CF Mestalla|reserves]] shortly after.<ref>[http://www.valenciacf.com/ver/19430/juan-pablo--nuevo-jugador-del-filial.html Juan Pablo, nuevo jugador del filial (Juan Pablo, new reserve team player)]; Valencia CF, 1 February 2010 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, after [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his last team's relegation]], Juan Pablo continued his career in division three, returning to former club \u00c9cija. He retired at the age of only 30 after becoming despondent with the sport, later working as manager and personal driver of [[Bullfighting|bullfighter]] Morante de la Puebla.<ref>[http://www.laverdad.es/murcia/deportes/201504/27/juan-pablo-quiso-heroe-20150427012735-v.html Juan Pablo no quiso ser un h\u00e9roe (Juan Pablo did not want to be a hero)]; La Verdad, 27 April 2015 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|6296|Juan Pablo}}\n*{{Soccerway|juan-pablo-ruiz-perez/62083|Juan Pablo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Juan Pablo Ruiz Perez}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Seville (comarca)]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Andalusian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Betis Deportivo Balompi\u00e9 footballers]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cija Balompi\u00e9 players]]\n[[Category:Algeciras CF footballers]]\n[[Category:Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico players]]\n[[Category:FC Cartagena footballers]]\n[[Category:Valencia CF Mestalla footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor tidyups overall, nothing hurt whatsoever.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Pablo_Ruiz_P%C3%A9rez"}
{"title_page": "Ilustrado", "text_new": "{{about||the Philippine TV series|Ilustrado (TV series)|the followers of ''Ilustraci\u00f3n''|Enlightenment in Spain}}\n[[File:Ilustrados 1890.jpg|thumb|300px|right|''Ilustrados'' in Madrid (c.1890)]]\nThe '''Ilustrados''' ({{IPA-es|ilus\u02c8t\u027ea\u00f0os|lang}}, \"erudite\",<ref>The American Heritage Spanish Dictionary (2nd ed.)</ref> \"learned\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buscon.rae.es/draeI/SrvltObtenerHtml?origen=RAE&LEMA=despotismo&SUPIND=0&CAREXT=10000&NEDIC=No#ilustrado.|title=Diccionario de la lengua espa\u00f1ola - Edici\u00f3n del Tricentenario|author=RAE - ASALE|work=Diccionario de la lengua espa\u00f1ola}}</ref> or \"enlightened ones\"<ref name=LOC/>) constituted the [[Filipino people|Filipino]] [[Education in the Philippines|educated]] class during the [[History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)|Spanish colonial period]] in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"Thomas2012\">{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Megan Christine|title=Orientalists, Propagandists, and Ilustrados: Filipino Scholarship and the End of Spanish Colonialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N5oXSfqr1AMC|year=2012|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|isbn=978-0-8166-7190-8|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=N5oXSfqr1AMC&pg=PA213&dq=ilustrado+philippines+century 213]}}</ref><ref name=\"Cullinane1989\">{{cite book|last=Cullinane|first=Michael|title=Ilustrado Politics: Filipino Elite Responses to American Rule, 1898-1908|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sjMa5dt7gTQC|year=1989|publisher=Ateneo University Press|isbn=978-971-550-439-3}}</ref> Elsewhere in [[New Spain]] (of which the Philippines were part), the term ''[[gente de raz\u00f3n]]'' carried a similar meaning.\n\nThey were the [[middle class]] who were educated in [[Spanish language in the Philippines|Spain]] and exposed to [[Spanish liberalism|Spanish liberal]] and European nationalist ideals. The ''Ilustrado'' class was composed of native-born intellectuals and cut across ethnolinguistic and racial lines&mdash;''[[Filipino people|Indios]]'', ''[[Criollo (people)|Insulares]]'' and ''[[Filipino mestizo|Mestizos]]'', among others&mdash;and sought [[reform]] through \"a more equitable arrangement of both political and economic power\" under Spanish tutelage.\n\n[[Stanley Karnow]], in his ''[[In Our Image: America's Empire in the Philippines]]'', referred to the ''Ilustrados'' as the \"rich [[Intelligentsia]]\" because many were the children of  wealthy landowners. They were key figures in the development of [[Filipino nationalism]].<ref name=LOC>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/philippines/ph_glos.html Glossary: Philippines, Area Handbook Series, Country Studies, Federal Research Division, Library of Congress, LOC.gov (undated)], retrieved on: July 30, 2007</ref><ref>[http://people.cohums.ohio-state.edu/grimsley1/milhis/phil.htm Grimsley, Mark. The Philippine War: 1899-1902, Ohio-State.edu, 1993, 1996] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009102022/http://people.cohums.ohio-state.edu/grimsley1/milhis/phil.htm |date=2012-10-09 }}, retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref><ref name=\"Karnow\">[[Stanley Karnow|Karnow, Stanley]]. ''[[In Our Image: America's Empire in the Philippines]]'', Ballantine Books, Random House, Inc., March 3, 1990, 536 pages, page 15.  -  {{ISBN|0-345-32816-7}}</ref><ref name=Mega>[http://www.megaessays.com/viewpaper/28063.html The Rise of the Philippine Middle Class (Ilustrados), Mega Essays LLC, MegaEssays.com, 2007], retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref><ref name=Britannica>[http://www.britannica.com/ebi/article-206427 Philippines: The Spanish Colony, Student Encyclopedia Article, Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online, Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc., Britannica.com], retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref><ref name=Embassy>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070713175511/http://www.philippineembassy-usa.org/about/history.htm#top  History of the Philippines], Embassy of the Republic of the Philippines, Department of Foreign Affairs, PhilippineEmbassy-USA.org (undated, archived from [http://www.philippineembassy-usa.org/about/history.htm the original] on 2007-07-13), retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Filipino Ilustrados Jose Rizal Marcelo del Pilar Mariano Ponce.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Three prominent ''Ilustrados'' in Spain: Dr. Jos\u00e9 Rizal, Marcelo H. del Pilar and Mariano Ponce ''(from left to right)''. Photo was taken in Spain in 1890.]]\n\nThe most prominent ''Ilustrados'' were [[Graciano L\u00f3pez Jaena]], [[Marcelo H. del Pilar]], [[Mariano Ponce]], [[Antonio Luna]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Rizal]], the Philippine [[Folk hero|national hero]].  Rizal's novels ''[[Noli Me Tangere (novel)|Noli Me Tangere]]'' (\"Touch Me Not\") and ''[[El filibusterismo|El Filibusterismo]]'' (\"The Subversive\") \"exposed to the world the injustices imposed on Filipinos under the Spanish colonial regime\".<ref name=Britannica/><ref name=SSPXAsia>[http://www.sspxasia.com/Newsletters/2002/Jan-Mar/Liberalism_in_the_Philippines.htm Salvador, Fr. Emerson, Liberalism in the Philippines, The Revolution of 1898: The Main Facts, Newsletter of the District of Asia, Society of St. Pius X, District of Asia, January - March 2002], retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref>\n\nIn the beginning, Rizal and his fellow ''Ilustrados'' preferred not to win [[Independence Day (Philippines)|independence]] from [[Spain]], instead they yearned legal equality for both ''[[Peninsulares]]'' and natives&mdash;''[[Filipino people|Indios]]'', ''[[Criollo (people)|Insulares]]'', and ''[[Filipino mestizo|mestizos]]'', among others&mdash;in the economic reforms demanded by the ''Ilustrados'' were that \"the Philippines be represented in the [[Cortes Generales|Cortes]] and be considered as a [[province]] of Spain\" and \"the [[Secular clergy|secularization of the parishes]].\"<ref name=Embassy/><ref name=SSPXAsia/>\n\nHowever, in 1872, nationalist sentiment grew strongest, when three Filipino [[priest]]s, [[Jos\u00e9 Burgos]], [[Mariano G\u00f3mez]] and [[friar]] [[Jacinto Zamora]], who had been charged with leading a military [[Cavite Mutiny|mutiny]] at an [[arsenal]] in [[Cavite]], near [[Manila]], were executed by the Spanish authorities. The event and \"other repressive acts outraitings and activities, Rizal was executed on December 30, 1896. His execution propelled the ''Ilustrados'' .  This also prompted unity among the ''Ilustrados'' and [[Andr\u00e9s Bonifacio]]'s radical ''[[Katipunan]]''.<ref name=Embassy/>  Philippine policies by the [[United States]] reinforced the dominant position of the ''Ilustrados'' within Filipino society. [[Friar]] estates were sold to the ''Ilustrados'' and most government positions were offered to them.<ref name=Embassy />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Spanish Filipino]]\n* [[Assimilado]]s\n* [[Ladino people]]\n* [[\u00c9volu\u00e9]]s\n* [[Affranchi]]s\n* [[Emancipados]]\n*[[Filipino nationalism]]\n*[[Spanish language in the Philippines]]\n*[[Philippine literature in Spanish]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/5kwrDWGCH?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761558570_11/Philippines.html Republic of the Philippines, Microsoft Corporation, Encarta.MSN.com, 2007] ( ([https://www.webcitation.org/5kwrDWGCH?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761558570_11/Philippines.html Archived] 2009-10-31), retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070613044936/http://www.smc.org.ph/apmj8-1.htm Exiles, Motherland and Social Change, Asian and Pacific Migration Journal (Bibliography), Volume 8, Issue 1-2, SMC.org.ph, (undated)], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2053260 Owen, Norman G., Compadre Colonialism: Studies in the Philippines Under American Rule, A Review by Theodore Friend, The Journal of Asian Studies, Vol. 32, No. 1 (Nov., 1972), pp. 224-226, JSTOR.org, 2007], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2754881 Majul, Cesar A. The Political and Constitutional Ideas of the Philippine Revolution, A Review by R. S. Milne, Pacific Affairs, Vol. 42, No. 1 (Spring, 1969), pp. 98-99, JSTOR.org, 2007], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[http://opmanong.ssc.hawaii.edu/filipino/republic.html Proclamation of Philippine Independence and the Birth of the Philippine Republic, The Philippine History Site, OpManong.SSC.Hawaii.edu (undated)], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070618190303/http://www.columbia.edu/cu/asiaweb/v11n1Rossabi.htm Rossabi, Amy. The Colonial Roots of Civil Procedure in the Philippines, Volume 11, Number 1, Fall 1997, The Journal of Asian Law, Columbia.edu], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/ca/doodz/philippines3.html Filipino Nationalism, AngelFire.com (undated)], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091026220228/http://geocities.com/centerforbulacanstudies/barasoain.html Veneracion, Jaime B., Ph. D. (Professor of History, University of the Philippines and Visiting Professor, BSU), Rizal's Madrid: The Roots of the Ilustrado Concept of Autonomy, Diyaryo Bulakenya, Bahay Saliksikan ng Bulakan (Center for Bulacan Studies), Geocities.com, April 4, 2003], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070813052804/http://www.philippinechildrensfoundation.org/history.shtml Philippine History, Philippine Children's Foundation, PhilippineChildrensFoundation.org, 2005], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)]]\n[[Category:Philippine Revolution]]\n[[Category:Latin American caste system]]\n[[Category:Captaincy General of the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the Philippine TV series|Ilustrado (TV series)|the followers of ''Ilustraci\u00f3n''|Enlightenment in Spain}}\n[[File:Ilustrados 1890.jpg|thumb|300px|right|''Ilustrados'' in Madrid (c.1890)]]\nThe '''Ilustrados''' ({{IPA-es|ilus\u02c8t\u027ea\u00f0os|lang}}, \"erudite\",<ref>The American Heritage Spanish Dictionary (2nd ed.)</ref> \"learned\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buscon.rae.es/draeI/SrvltObtenerHtml?origen=RAE&LEMA=despotismo&SUPIND=0&CAREXT=10000&NEDIC=No#ilustrado.|title=Diccionario de la lengua espa\u00f1ola - Edici\u00f3n del Tricentenario|author=RAE - ASALE|work=Diccionario de la lengua espa\u00f1ola}}</ref> or \"enlightened ones\"<ref name=LOC/>) constituted the [[Filipino people|Filipino]] [[Education in the Philippines|educated]] class during the [[History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)|Spanish colonial period]] in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"Thomas2012\">{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Megan Christine|title=Orientalists, Propagandists, and Ilustrados: Filipino Scholarship and the End of Spanish Colonialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N5oXSfqr1AMC|year=2012|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|isbn=978-0-8166-7190-8|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=N5oXSfqr1AMC&pg=PA213&dq=ilustrado+philippines+century 213]}}</ref><ref name=\"Cullinane1989\">{{cite book|last=Cullinane|first=Michael|title=Ilustrado Politics: Filipino Elite Responses to American Rule, 1898-1908|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sjMa5dt7gTQC|year=1989|publisher=Ateneo University Press|isbn=978-971-550-439-3}}</ref> Elsewhere in [[New Spain]] (of which the Philippines were part), the term ''[[gente de raz\u00f3n]]'' carried a similar meaning.\n\nThey were the [[middle class]] who were educated in [[Spanish language in the Philippines|Spain]] and exposed to [[Spanish liberalism|Spanish liberal]] and European nationalist ideals. The ''Ilustrado'' class was composed of native-born intellectuals and cut across ethnolinguistic and racial lines&mdash;''[[Filipino people|Indios]]'', ''[[Criollo (people)|Insulares]]'' and ''[[Filipino mestizo|Mestizos]]'', among others&mdash;and sought [[reform]] through \"a more equitable arrangement of both political and economic power\" under Spanish tutelage.\n\n[[Stanley Karnow]], in his ''[[In Our Image: America's Empire in the Philippines]]'', referred to the ''Ilustrados'' as the \"rich [[Intelligentsia]]\" because many were the children of  wealthy landowners. They were key figures in the development of [[Filipino nationalism]].<ref name=LOC>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/philippines/ph_glos.html Glossary: Philippines, Area Handbook Series, Country Studies, Federal Research Division, Library of Congress, LOC.gov (undated)], retrieved on: July 30, 2007</ref><ref>[http://people.cohums.ohio-state.edu/grimsley1/milhis/phil.htm Grimsley, Mark. The Philippine War: 1899-1902, Ohio-State.edu, 1993, 1996] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009102022/http://people.cohums.ohio-state.edu/grimsley1/milhis/phil.htm |date=2012-10-09 }}, retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref><ref name=\"Karnow\">[[Stanley Karnow|Karnow, Stanley]]. ''[[In Our Image: America's Empire in the Philippines]]'', Ballantine Books, Random House, Inc., March 3, 1990, 536 pages, page 15.  -  {{ISBN|0-345-32816-7}}</ref><ref name=Mega>[http://www.megaessays.com/viewpaper/28063.html The Rise of the Philippine Middle Class (Ilustrados), Mega Essays LLC, MegaEssays.com, 2007], retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref><ref name=Britannica>[http://www.britannica.com/ebi/article-206427 Philippines: The Spanish Colony, Student Encyclopedia Article, Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online, Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc., Britannica.com], retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref><ref name=Embassy>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070713175511/http://www.philippineembassy-usa.org/about/history.htm#top  History of the Philippines], Embassy of the Republic of the Philippines, Department of Foreign Affairs, PhilippineEmbassy-USA.org (undated, archived from [http://www.philippineembassy-usa.org/about/history.htm the original] on 2007-07-13), retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Filipino Ilustrados Jose Rizal Marcelo del Pilar Mariano Ponce.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Three prominent ''Ilustrados'' in Spain: Dr. Jos\u00e9 Rizal, Marcelo H. del Pilar and Mariano Ponce ''(from left to right)''. Photo was taken in Spain in 1890.]]\n\nThe most prominent ''Ilustrados'' were [[Graciano L\u00f3pez Jaena]], [[Marcelo H. del Pilar]], [[Mariano Ponce]], [[Antonio Luna]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Rizal]], the Philippine [[Folk hero|national hero]].  Rizal's novels ''[[Noli Me Tangere (novel)|Noli Me Tangere]]'' (\"Touch Me Not\") and ''[[El filibusterismo|El Filibusterismo]]'' (\"The Subversive\") \"exposed to the world the injustices imposed on Filipinos under the Spanish colonial regime\".<ref name=Britannica/><ref name=SSPXAsia>[http://www.sspxasia.com/Newsletters/2002/Jan-Mar/Liberalism_in_the_Philippines.htm Salvador, Fr. Emerson, Liberalism in the Philippines, The Revolution of 1898: The Main Facts, Newsletter of the District of Asia, Society of St. Pius X, District of Asia, January - March 2002], retrieved on: August 1, 2007</ref>\n\nIn the beginning, Rizal and his fellow ''Ilustrados'' preferred not to win [[Independence Day (Philippines)|independence]] from [[Spain]], instead they yearned legal equality for both ''[[Peninsulares]]'' and natives&mdash;''[[Filipino people|Indios]]'', ''[[Criollo (people)|Insulares]]'', and ''[[Filipino mestizo|mestizos]]'', among others&mdash;in the economic reforms demanded by the ''Ilustrados'' were that \"the Philippines be represented in the [[Cortes Generales|Cortes]] and be considered as a [[province]] of Spain\" and \"the [[Secular clergy|secularization of the parishes]].\"<ref name=Embassy/><ref name=SSPXAsia/>\n\nHowever, in 1872, nationalist sentiment grew strongest, when three Filipino [[priest]]s, [[Jos\u00e9 Burgos]], [[Mariano G\u00f3mez]] and [[friar]] [[Jacinto Zamora]], who had been charged with leading a military [[Cavite Mutiny|mutiny]] at an [[arsenal]] in [[Cavite]], near [[Manila]], were executed by the Spanish authorities. The event and \"other repressive acts outraitings and activities, Rizal was executed on December 30, 1896. His execution propelled the ''Ilustrados'' .  This also prompted unity among the ''Ilustrados'' and [[Andr\u00e9s Bonifacio]]'s radical ''[[Katipunan]]''.<ref name=Embassy/>  Philippine policies by the [[United States]] reinforced the dominant position of the ''Ilustrados'' within Filipino society. [[Friar]] estates were sold to the ''Ilustrados'' and most government positions were offered to them.<ref name=Embassy />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Assimilado]]s\n* [[Ladino people]]\n* [[\u00c9volu\u00e9]]s\n* [[Affranchi]]s\n* [[Emancipados]]\n*[[Filipino nationalism]]\n*[[Spanish language in the Philippines]]\n*[[Philippine literature in Spanish]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/5kwrDWGCH?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761558570_11/Philippines.html Republic of the Philippines, Microsoft Corporation, Encarta.MSN.com, 2007] ( ([https://www.webcitation.org/5kwrDWGCH?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761558570_11/Philippines.html Archived] 2009-10-31), retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070613044936/http://www.smc.org.ph/apmj8-1.htm Exiles, Motherland and Social Change, Asian and Pacific Migration Journal (Bibliography), Volume 8, Issue 1-2, SMC.org.ph, (undated)], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2053260 Owen, Norman G., Compadre Colonialism: Studies in the Philippines Under American Rule, A Review by Theodore Friend, The Journal of Asian Studies, Vol. 32, No. 1 (Nov., 1972), pp. 224-226, JSTOR.org, 2007], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2754881 Majul, Cesar A. The Political and Constitutional Ideas of the Philippine Revolution, A Review by R. S. Milne, Pacific Affairs, Vol. 42, No. 1 (Spring, 1969), pp. 98-99, JSTOR.org, 2007], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[http://opmanong.ssc.hawaii.edu/filipino/republic.html Proclamation of Philippine Independence and the Birth of the Philippine Republic, The Philippine History Site, OpManong.SSC.Hawaii.edu (undated)], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070618190303/http://www.columbia.edu/cu/asiaweb/v11n1Rossabi.htm Rossabi, Amy. The Colonial Roots of Civil Procedure in the Philippines, Volume 11, Number 1, Fall 1997, The Journal of Asian Law, Columbia.edu], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/ca/doodz/philippines3.html Filipino Nationalism, AngelFire.com (undated)], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091026220228/http://geocities.com/centerforbulacanstudies/barasoain.html Veneracion, Jaime B., Ph. D. (Professor of History, University of the Philippines and Visiting Professor, BSU), Rizal's Madrid: The Roots of the Ilustrado Concept of Autonomy, Diyaryo Bulakenya, Bahay Saliksikan ng Bulakan (Center for Bulacan Studies), Geocities.com, April 4, 2003], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070813052804/http://www.philippinechildrensfoundation.org/history.shtml Philippine History, Philippine Children's Foundation, PhilippineChildrensFoundation.org, 2005], retrieved on: August 1, 2007\n\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)]]\n[[Category:Philippine Revolution]]\n[[Category:Latin American caste system]]\n[[Category:Captaincy General of the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "Juanmakabulos", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ilustrado"}
{"title_page": "Hyacinth macaw", "text_new": "{{about|the bird|the play by Mac Wellman|The Hyacinth Macaw}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Hyacinth macaw\n| image = Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -Disney -Florida-8.jpg\n| image_caption = At the [[Disney's Animal Kingdom Park]], Florida\n| status = VU  <!-- Do NOT change this to \"extinct\" here or make any such changes in the text unless you can provide authoritative sources that definitely state so. In any case, do NOT change present tense to past tense \u2013 a species still \"IS\" a species even when it has become extinct. -->\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International. (2016) ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016. {{DOI|10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22685516A93077457.en}}</ref>\n| genus = Anodorhynchus\n| species = hyacinthinus\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790)\n| range_map = Hyacinth area.png\n}}\n\nThe '''hyacinth macaw''' (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''), or '''hyacinthine macaw''', is a [[parrot]] native to central and eastern [[South America]]. With a length (from the top of its head to the tip of its long pointed tail) of about one meter (3.3&nbsp;ft) it is longer than any other species of parrot. It is the largest [[macaw]] and the largest flying parrot species, though the flightless [[kakapo]] of New Zealand can outweigh it at up to 3.5&nbsp;kg. While generally easily recognized, it could be confused with the smaller [[Lear's macaw]]. Habitat loss and the trapping of wild birds for the pet trade have taken a heavy toll on their population in the wild, so the species is classified as [[Vulnerable species|Vulnerable]] on the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]]'s [[IUCN Red List|Red List]],<ref name=IUCN /> and it is protected by its listing on Appendix I of the [[Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora]] (CITES).\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nEnglish physician, ornithologist, and artist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] first described the hyacinth macaw in 1790 under the [[binomial name]] ''Psittacus hyacinthinus'' based on a taxidermic specimen sent to England.<ref>{{cite book| last= Latham| first= John | year=1790 | title= Index Ornithologicus, Sive Systema Ornithologiae: Complectens Avium Divisionem in Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, Ipsarumque Varietates (Volume 1) | language=Latin | place=London | publisher = Leigh & Sotheby | page=84 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QV5UAAAAcAAJ&pg=PT107}}</ref> It is one of two extant and one probably extinct species of the South American macaw genus ''[[Anodorhynchus]]''.\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Hyacinth Macaw head.jpg|205px|thumb|left|Close-up of head]]\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus ZOO Dvur Kralove.jpg|right|thumb|205px|A skeleton exhibited at [[Dv\u016fr Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9 Zoo]] in [[Dv\u016fr Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9 nad Labem]], Czech Republic]]\nThe largest parrot by length in the world, the hyacinth macaw is {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long from the tip of its tail to the top of its head and weighs {{convert|1.2|\u2013|1.7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 70.\">Forshaw (2006). plate 70.</ref><ref name=\"animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu\">Hagan, E. (2004). [http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Anodorhynchus_hyacinthinus.html ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'']. Animal Diversity Web</ref> Each wing is {{convert|38.8|-|42.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 70.\" /> The tail is long and pointed.<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 70.\" /> Its feathers are entirely blue, lighter above. However, the neck feathers can sometimes be slightly grey. The ring around the parrots eyes and area just underneath the beak are a strong, vibrant yellow.\n\n== Behaviour ==\n\n=== Food and feeding ===\n[[File:Hyacinth macaw (Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus) head.JPG|thumb|upright|231px|A hyacinth macaw eating nut at [[Pantanal]] in Brazil]]\nThe majority of the hyacinth macaw diet is Brazil nuts, from native palms, such as acuri and bocaiuva palms.<ref name=\"WWF\">{{cite web|title=Hyacinth Macaw| url=http://www.wwf.org.br/english/informa/sitearara_arara.htm|publisher=[[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021104224234/http://www.wwf.org.br/english/informa/sitearara_arara.htm |archivedate=2002-11-04 |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref> They have very strong beaks for eating the kernels of hard [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] and seeds. Their strong beaks are even able to crack [[coconut]]s, the large [[brazil nut]] pods, and [[macadamia nut]]s. The birds also boast dry, smooth tongues with a bone inside them that makes them an effective tool for tapping into fruits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Macaw ''Psittacidae'' | url=http://animals.nationalgeographic.com/animals/birds/macaw/| publisher=National Geographic | accessdate=24 October 2013| date=2010-11-11}}</ref> The [[acuri]] nut is so hard, the parrots cannot feed on it until it has passed through the digestive system of cattle.<ref name=\"WWF\" /> In addition, they eat [[fruit]]s and other vegetable matter. The hyacinth macaw generally eats fruits, nuts, nectar, and various kinds of seeds. Also, they travel for the ripest of foods over a vast area.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Real Macaw Endangered Tropical Jewels | url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/nature/episodes/the-real-macaw/endangered-tropical-jewels/2734/ | publisher=Public Broadcasting Service | date=26 February 2004 | accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Pantanal]], hyacinth macaws feed almost exclusively on the nuts of ''[[Acrocomia aculeata]]'' and ''[[Attalea phalerata]]'' palm trees. This behaviour was recorded by the English [[natural history|naturalist]] [[Henry Walter Bates]] in his 1863 book ''[[The Naturalist on the River Amazons]]'', where he wrote that\n\n{{quote|It flies in pairs, and feeds on the hard nuts of several palms, but especially of the Mucuja (''[[Acrocomia aculeata|Acrocomia lasiospatha]]''). These nuts, which are so hard as to be difficult to break with a heavy hammer, are crushed to a pulp by the powerful beak of this macaw.|Bates<ref>{{ cite book | last=Bates | first=Henry Walter | author-link=Henry Walter Bates | year=1863 | title=The naturalist on the River Amazons, Volume 1 | volume=1 | publisher=John Murray | place=London | page=133 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/18557093}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Charles Darwin]] remarked on Bates's account of the species, calling it a \"splendid bird\" with its \"enormous beak\" able to feed on these palm nuts.<ref name=DarwinApp>{{cite web | url=http://www.lepidopterology.com/almanac/display.php?q=bates-amazon | title=An Appreciation: The Naturalist on the River Amazons by Henry Walter Bates | publisher=Natural History Review, vol iii | year=1863 | accessdate=27 March 2013 | author=Darwin, Charles | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607200303/http://www.lepidopterology.com/almanac/display.php?q=bates-amazon | archive-date=7 June 2011 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Tool use ===\nLimited tool use has been observed in both wild and captive hyacinth macaws. Reported sightings of tool use in wild parrots go as far back as 1863. Examples of tool use that have been observed usually involve a chewed leaf or pieces of wood. Macaws often incorporate these items when feeding on harder nuts. Their use allows the nuts the macaws eat to remain in position (prevent slipping) while they gnaw into it. It is not known whether this is learned social behavior or an innate trait, but observation on captive macaws shows that hand-raised macaws exhibit this behavior, as well. Comparisons show that older macaws were able to open seeds more efficiently.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1007/s10071-004-0221-3|pmid=15248094|title=Preliminary observations of tool use in captive hyacinth macaws (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'')|journal=Animal Cognition|volume=8|issue=1|pages=48\u201352|year=2004|last1=Borsari|first1=Andressa|last2=Ottoni|first2=Eduardo B.}}</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -Mato Grosso do Sul, Brazil -nest-8 (3).jpg|right|thumb|A pair in their nest]]\nNesting takes place between July and December, with nests constructed in tree cavities or cliff faces depending on the habitat.<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> In the Pantanal region, 90% of nests are constructed in the manduvi tree (''[[Sterculia apetala]]''). The hyacinth macaw depends on the [[toucan]], for its livelihood. The toucan contributes largely to seed dispersal of the manduvi tree that the macaw needs for reproduction.<ref name=Pizo08>{{cite journal|last1=Pizo|first1=Marco A.|first2=Camila I. |last2= Donatti|first3=Neiva R. |last3= Guedes|first4=Mauro |last4=Galetti|title=Conservation Puzzle: Endangered Hyacinth Macaw Depends on Its Nest Predator for Reproduction|journal=Biological Conservation |url=http://web.me.com/galetti/Labic/Publications_files/Pizo_Donatti_Galetti_BiolConserv2008_Conservartion%20puzzle%20endangered%20macaw%20depends%20on%20its%20nest%20predator%20for%20reproduction.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2007.12.023|volume=141|issue=3| year=2008|pages= 792\u201396|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref> However, the toucan is responsible for dispersing 83% of the seeds of ''Sterculia apetala'', but also consumes 53% of eggs preyed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hyacinth Macaw Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus| url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=1543|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref> Hollows of sufficient size are only found in trees around 60 years of age or older, and competition is fierce.<ref name= Pizo08 /> Existing holes are enlarged and then partially filled with wood chips.<ref name=\"MB WWF\">{{cite web| url= http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/conservation/species_programme/species_news/species_news_archive.cfm?12641/The-hyacinth-macaw-makes-a-comeback |first=Meindert |last=Brouwer|title=The hyacinth macaw makes a comeback |publisher=WWF|accessdate=20 July 2011 |date=21 April 2004}}</ref> The clutch size is one or two [[Egg (biology)|eggs]],<ref name=\"WWF\" /> although usually only one fledgling survives<ref name=\"WWF\" /> as the second egg hatches several days after the first, and the smaller fledgling cannot compete with the firstborn for food. A possible explanation for this behavior is what is called the insurance hypothesis. The macaw lays more eggs than can be normally fledged to compensate for earlier eggs that failed to hatch or firstborn chicks that did not survive.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kuniy|first= A.|title=Handling technique to increase the hyacinth macaw population (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') (Lalham, 1720) \u2013 Report of an experience in Pantanal, Brazil|pmid=16710531|doi=10.1590/S1519-69842006000200021 |journal=Brazilian Journal of Biology|volume= 66|issue= 1B| year= 2006| pages=381\u201382}}</ref> The incubation period lasts about a month, and the male tends to his mate whilst she incubates the eggs.<ref name=\"WWF\" /> [http://petconearme1.com The chicks] leave the nest, or fledge, around 110 days of age,<ref name=\"Allgayer2009\" /> and remain dependent on their parents until six months of age.<ref name=\"WWF\" /> They are mature and begin breeding at seven years of age.\n\n=== General traits ===\nHyacinth macaws are the largest psittacine. They are also very even-tempered and can be calmer than other macaws, being known as \"gentle giants\".<ref name=\"Kalhagen\">{{cite web|last=Kalhagen|first=Alyson|title=Hyacinth Macaws|url=http://birds.about.com/od/breedsofbirds/p/hyacinths.htm| work=Pet Birds | publisher=About.com|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> An attending veterinarian must be aware of specific nutritional needs and pharmacologic sensitivities when dealing with them. Possibly due to genetic factors or captive rearing limitations, this species can become neurotic/phobic, which is problematic.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lennox|first=Angela| pages=35 | chapterurl=http://old.trustedpartner.com/docs/library/000087/02companion.pdf|title=Clinical Avian Medicine, Volume 1 |chapter=The companion bird}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus wild.jpg|thumb|left|Hyacinth macaws in their natural [[habitat]], the [[Pantanal]], Brazil]]\nThe hyacinth macaw survives today in three main populations in [[South America]]: In the [[Pantanal]] region of [[Brazil]], and adjacent eastern [[Bolivia]] and northeastern [[Paraguay]], in the [[Cerrado]] region of the eastern interior of Brazil ([[Maranh\u00e3o]], [[Piau\u00ed]], [[Bahia]], [[Tocantins]], [[Goi\u00e1s]], [[Mato Grosso]], [[Mato Grosso do Sul]], and [[Minas Gerais]]), and in the relatively open areas associated with the [[Tocantins River]], [[Xingu River]], [[Tapaj\u00f3s River]], and the [[Maraj\u00f3]] island in the eastern [[Amazon Basin]] of Brazil. Smaller, fragmented populations may occur in other areas. It prefers [[Arecaceae|palm]] [[swamp]]s, woodlands, and other semiopen, wooded habitats. It usually avoids dense, humid forest, and in regions dominated by such habitats, it is generally restricted to the edge or relatively open sections (e.g. along major rivers). In different areas of their range, these parrots are found in savannah grasslands, in dry thorn forest known as [[caatinga]], and in palm stands,<ref name=\"Birdlife\">{{cite web |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=1543 |title=Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''): BirdLife species factsheet |publisher=[[BirdLife International]] |accessdate=19 September 2013}} \u2013 via [[ARKive]]</ref> particularly the [[Moriche Palm]] (''Mauritia flexuosa'').<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 95.\">Forshaw (2006). page 95.</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\nThe hyacinth macaw has escaped or been deliberately released in to [[Florida]], USA, but there is no evidence that the population is breeding and may only persist due to continuing releases or escapes.[http://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/nonnatives/birds/hyacinth-macaw/]\n\n== Conservation and threats ==\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -zoo de La Palmyre-8a.jpg|thumb|Captive macaw at [[La Palmyre Zoo]], [[France]]]]\nThe hyacinth macaw is an endangered species due to the cage bird trade and [[habitat loss]].<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> In the 1980s, an estimated 10,000 birds were taken from the wild and at least 50% were destined for the Brazilian market.<ref name=Mittermeier>{{cite web|title=Hyacinth Macaw Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=1543|accessdate=25 October 2013|year=1990|website=birdlife.org}}</ref> Throughout the macaw's range, habitat is being lost or altered due to the introduction of cattle ranching and mechanised agriculture, and the development of hydroelectric schemes.<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> Annual grass fires set by farmers can destroy nest trees, and regions previously inhabited by this macaw are now unsuitable also due to [[agriculture]] and plantations. Locally, it has been hunted for food, and the [[Kayapo]] Indians of Gorotire in south-central Brazil use its [[feather]]s to make headdresses and other ornaments. While overall greatly reduced in numbers, it remains locally common in the Brazilian Pantanal, where many ranch-owners now protect the macaws on their land.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.arkive.org/hyacinth-macaw/anodorhynchus-hyacinthinus/| title= Hyacinth macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'')| website= arkive.org| accessdate= 11 August 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150905060327/http://www.arkive.org/hyacinth-macaw/anodorhynchus-hyacinthinus/| archive-date= 5 September 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe hyacinth macaw is protected by law in Brazil and Bolivia,<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> and commercial export is banned by its listing on Appendix I of the [[Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species|CITES]].<ref name=\"CITES\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cites.org/eng/app/ |title=The CITES Appendices |publisher=[[CITES]] |accessdate=19 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055732/http://www.cites.org/eng/app/ |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A number of long-term studies and conservation initiatives are in place; the Hyacinth Macaw Project in the Brazilian state of Mato Grosso do Sul has carried out important research by ringing individual birds, and has created a number of artificial nests to compensate for the small number of sites available in the region.<ref name=\"WWF\" />\n\nThe [[Minnesota Zoo]] with BioBrasil and the [[World Wildlife Fund]] are involved in hyacinth macaw conservation.<ref name=\"MB WWF\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnzoo.com/conservation/conservation_world_hyMacaw.asp|title= BioBrasil and the Minnesota Zoo working to save Hyacinth Macaws|publisher=Minnesota Zoo |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Causes of endangerment ===\nParrots as a whole, being of the family [[Psittacidae]], are some of the most threatened birds in the world. This family has the most endangered species of all bird families, especially in the [[neotropics]], the natural home of the hyacinth macaw, where 46 of 145 species are at a serious risk of global extinction.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Nest Poaching in Neotropical Parrots|journal=Conservation Biology |volume = 15 | issue = 3|pages=710\u2013720 | date = June 2001 | first1 = Timothy F. | last1 = Wright | first2 = Catherine A. | last2 = Toft | first3 = Ernesto | last3 = Enkerlin-Hoeflich | first4 = Jaime | last4 = Gonzalez-Elizondo | first5 = Mariana | last5 = Albornoz | first6 = Adriana | last6 = Rodr\u00edguez-Ferraro | first7 = Franklin | last7 = Rojas-Su\u00e1rez | first8 = Virginia | last8 = Sanz | first9 = Ana | last9 = Trujillo | first10 = Steven R. | last10 = Biessinger | first11 = Vincente | last11 = Berovidas A. |url = https://nature.berkeley.edu/beislab/BeissingerLab/publications/Wright_etal_2001_ConsBio.pdf |doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.2001.015003710.x}}</ref> This species qualifies as 'Vulnerable' on the [[IUCN Red List]] because the population has suffered rapid reductions with the remaining threats of illegal trapping for the cage bird trade and habitat loss <ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\">[http://eol.org/pages/1177958/overview ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'': Hyacinth Macaw]. 2013. [[Encyclopedia of Life]].</ref> A few serious threats to the survival of the species in the Pantanal include human activities, mainly those resulting in habitat loss, the burning of land for pasture maintenance, and illegal trapping <ref>{{cite journal|author=Pinho, J. B.|author2=Nogueira, Flavia M. B.|last-author-amp=yes |year=2003|title=Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') reproduction in the northern Pantanal, Mato Grosso, Brazil|url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/119497|journal= Ornitologia Neotropical |volume=14|pages= 29\u201338}}</ref> The exceptionally noisy, fearless, curious, sedentary, and predictable nature of this species, along with its specialization to only one or two species of palm in each part of its range, makes them especially vulnerable to capture, shooting, and [[habitat destruction]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|author=Collar, N. J.|author2=Juniper, A. T.|last-author-amp=yes |title= Dimensions and Causes of the Parrot Conservation Crisis|url=http://people.ds.cam.ac.uk/cns26/njc/Papers/Parrot%20crisis.PDF|publisher= International Council for Bird Preservation |pages=1\u20136, 9, 12\u201315, 19}}</ref> Eggs are also regularly preyed on by [[corvid]]s, [[opossum]]s, and [[coati]]s.<ref>[http://news.mongabay.com/2008/0313-hance_macaws.html Predator of the world's largest macaw key to its survival] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604144418/http://news.mongabay.com/2008/0313-hance_macaws.html |date=4 June 2009 }}. news.mongabay.com (2008-03-13)</ref> Adults have no known natural predators.<ref name=\"animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu\" /> The young are parasitized by larvae of flies of the genus ''[[Philornis]]''.<ref name=\"Allgayer2009\">{{cite journal|author=Allgayer, M. C.|author2=Guedes, N. M. R.|author3=Chiminazzo, C.|author4=Cziulik, M.|author5=Weimer, T. A. |year=2009|title=Clinical Pathology and Parasitologic Evaluation of Free Living Nestlings of the Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'')|journal=Journal of Wildlife Diseases|volume=45|issue=4|pages=972\u201381|pmid=19901373 |doi=10.7589/0090-3558-45.4.972}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the species has a low genetic variability, it does not necessarily pose a threat to their survival. This genetic structure accentuates the need for protection of hyacinth macaws from different regions to maintain their genetic diversity. Nevertheless, the most important factors negatively affecting the wild population prove to be [[habitat destruction]] and nest poaching.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1007/s10531-007-9312-1|year= 2008|title=Genetic variation and population structure of the endangered Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''): implications for conservation|journal= Biodiversity and Conservation|volume= 17|issue= 4|pages= 765|last1= Faria|first1= Patr\u00edcia J.|last2= Guedes|first2= Neiva M. R.|last3= Yamashita|first3= Carlos|last4= Martuscelli|first4= Paulo|last5= Miyaki|first5= Cristina Y.}}</ref>\n\nIn the Pantanal, habitat loss is largely contributed to the creations of pastures for cattle, while in many other regions, it is the result of clearing land for colonization.<ref name=\"Tania F. R 2006\">{{cite journal|author=Tania F. R|author2=Glaucia H. F. R.|author3=Nevia M. R. G.|author4=Aramis A. G. |title= ''Chlamydophila psittaci'' in free-living Blue-fronted Amazon parrots (''Amazona aestiva'') and Hyacinth macaws (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') in the Pantanal of Mato Grosso do Sul, Brazil|journal= Veterinary Microbiology|volume= 117|issue= 2\u20134|pages= 235\u201341|pmid=16893616|year= 2006|doi= 10.1016/j.vetmic.2006.06.025}}</ref> Similarly, large areas of habitat in Amazonia have been lost for cattle ranching and hydroelectric power schemes on the Tocantins and Xingu Rivers. Many young manduvi trees are then being grazed on by cattle or burnt by fire, and the Gerias is speedily being converted to land for mechanized agriculture, cattle ranching, and exotic tree plantations.<ref name=IUCN /> Annual grass fires set by farmers destroy a number of nest trees, and the rise of agriculture and plantations has made habitats formerly populated by the macaws unsuitable to maintain their livelihoods.<ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\" /> Moreover, increase in commercial demand for feather art by the Kayapo Indians threatens the species, as up to 10 macaws are needed to make a single headdress.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nIn the event of the macaws being taken from their natural environment, a variety of factors alter their health such as inadequate hygiene conditions, feeding, and overpopulation during the illegal practice of pet trade. Once birds are captured and brought into captivity, their mortality rates can become very high.<ref name=\"Tania F. R 2006\" /> Records reveal a Paraguayan dealer receiving 300 unfeathered young in 1972, with all but three not surviving. Due to the poor survival rates of the young, poachers concentrate more heavily on adult birds, which depletes the population at a rapid pace.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nAccording to Article 111 of Bolivian Environmental Law #1333, all persons involved in the trade, capture, and transportation without authorization of wild animals will suffer a two-year prison sentence, along with a fine equivalent to 100% of the value of the animal.<ref name=\"Luecker, H. 2000\">{{cite journal|author=L\u00fccker, H.|author2=Patzwahl, S.|last-author-amp=yes |title= The European Endangered Species Programme (EEP) for the Hyacinth macaw ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'' from 1989 to 1998|journal= International Zoo Yearbook|volume= 37|pages= 178\u2013183|doi=10.1111/j.1748-1090.2000.tb00720.x|year= 2000}}</ref> While many trackers have been arrested, the illegal pet trade still largely continues in Santa Cruz, Bolivia. Unfortunately, animal trafficking is not necessarily viewed as a priority in the city, leaving national departmental and municipal governments unwilling to halt the trade in city centers, and local police reluctant to get involved. This ideology has in turn resulted in a lack of enforcement regarding trade in both CITES-restricted species and threatened species, with little to no restrictions regarding humane treatment of the animals, disease control, or proper hygiene. In the trade centers, the hyacinth macaw demanded the highest price of US$1,000, proving it to be a very desirable and valued bird in the pet trade industry.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Mauricio, H.|author2=Hennessey, B.|last-author-amp=yes |title=Quantifying the illegal parrot trade in Santa Cruz de la Sierra, Bolivia, with emphasis on threatened species|journal=Bird Conservation International|volume=17|issue=4|pages=295\u2013300|doi=10.1017/S0959270907000858 |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservation steps taken to preserve the hyacinth macaw ===\n\nIn 1989, the [[European Endangered Species Programme]] for the hyacinth macaw was founded as a result of concerns about the status of the wild population and the lack of successful breeding in captivity.<ref name=\"Luecker, H. 2000\" /> Breeding in captivity still remains difficult, being that hand-reared hyacinth macaw offspring have demonstrated to have higher mortality rates, especially within the first month of life. Additionally, they have a higher incidence of acute crop stasis than other macaw species due, in part, to their specific dietary requirements.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Casares, M.|author2=F. Enders|year= 1998|title= Experiences in the hand-rearing of hyacinth macaws (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') in Loro Parque|journal= Zoologische Garten |volume=68|pages= 65\u201374}}</ref> The hyacinth macaw is protected by law in Brazil and Bolivia, and international trade is prohibited by its listing on Appendix I of the CITES.<ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\" /> Appendix I has banned exporting the bird in all countries of origin, and several studies and conservational initiatives have been taken.<ref name=IUCN /> The Hyacinth Macaw Project in the Caiman Ecological Refuge, located in the Pantanal, has employed artificial nests and chick management techniques, along with effectively raising awareness among cattle ranchers. Many ranch owners in the Pantanal and Gerais, to protect the birds, no longer allow trappers on their properties.<ref name=IUCN />\n\nA number of conservation actions have been proposed, including the study of the current range, population status, and extent of trading in different parts of its range. Additionally, propositions have been made to assess the effectiveness of artificial nest boxes, enforce legal measures preventing trade, and experiment with ecotourism at one or two sites to encourage donors.<ref name=IUCN /> Furthermore, the Hyacinth Macaw Project in Mato Grosso do Sul has carried out important research by ringing individual birds and has created a number of artificial nests to compensate for the small number of sites available in the region.<ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\" /> Furthermore, proposals to list the species as Endangered under the U.S. Endangered Species Act have been made to further protective measures in the US and to create Bolivian and Paraguayan trade management authorities under presidential control.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n=== Long-term prospects ===\nEach of the three main populations should be managed as a separate biological entity so as to avoid numbers dropping below 500. While the birds may be in decline in the wild, notably higher populations of captive macaws are being held in zoos and private collections. If success in managing and replanting the macaw's food trees and erecting nest boxes as an experiment in the Pantanals is seen, the species could survive. Survival rates could also be enhanced if ranch owners would leave all large and potential nest trees standing and eliminate all trapping on their properties. Ultimately, should these factors work in tandem with erection of nest boxes, fencing off of certain saplings, and the planting of others, the long-term prospects of the hyacinth macaw species would be greatly improved.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"130px\">\nHyacinth macaws (Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus) 2.jpg\nHyacinth macaw (Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus) in flight.JPG\nFile:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -pet parrot-8a.jpg|Pet hyacinth macaw on arm\nFile:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -pet on bike handlebars-8.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of macaws]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n* {{Cite book |first=Joseph M. |last=Forshaw |authorlink=Joseph Forshaw |title=Parrots of the World; an Identification Guide |others=Illustrated by [[Frank Knight (artist)|Frank Knight]] |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |isbn=978-0-691-09251-5 |nopp=yes |year=2006 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/parrotsofworldid0000fors }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/hyacinth-macaw-anodorhynchus-hyacinthinus Hyacinth macaw] on the Internet Bird Collection\n* {{ARKive}}\n* [http://www.bluemacaws.org/ The Blue Macaws website]\n* [http://www.macaw-facts.com/species/blue-macaw-hyacinth-macaw-hyacinthine-macaw/ In-Depth Blue Macaw Research]\n* [http://www.freesound.org/samplesViewSingle.php?id=56513 Audio File of the hyacinth macaw]\n\n{{Macaws}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q463154}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:macaw, hyacinth}}\n[[Category:Anodorhynchus|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Macaws|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Talking birds]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Cerrado]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Pantanal]]\n[[Category:Birds of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Species endangered by habitat loss]]\n[[Category:Species endangered by the pet trade]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the bird|the play by Mac Wellman|The Hyacinth Macaw}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Hyacinth macaw\n| image = Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -Disney -Florida-8.jpg\n| image_caption = At the [[Disney's Animal Kingdom Park]], Florida\n| status = VU  <!-- Do NOT change this to \"extinct\" here or make any such changes in the text unless you can provide authoritative sources that definitely state so. In any case, do NOT change present tense to past tense \u2013 a species still \"IS\" a species even when it has become extinct. -->\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International. (2016) ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016. {{DOI|10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22685516A93077457.en}}</ref>\n| genus = Anodorhynchus\n| species = hyacinthinus\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790)\n| range_map = Hyacinth area.png\n}}\n\nThe '''hyacinth macaw''' (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''), or '''hyacinthine macaw''', is a [[parrot]] native to central and eastern [[South America]]. With a length (from the top of its head to the tip of its long pointed tail) of about one meter (3.3&nbsp;ft) it is longer than any other species of parrot. It is the largest [[macaw]] and the largest flying parrot species, though the flightless [[kakapo]] of New Zealand can outweigh it at up to 3.5&nbsp;kg. While generally easily recognized, it could be confused with the smaller [[Lear's macaw]]. Habitat loss and the trapping of wild birds for the pet trade have taken a heavy toll on their population in the wild, so the species is classified as [[Vulnerable species|Vulnerable]] on the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]]'s [[IUCN Red List|Red List]],<ref name=IUCN /> and it is protected by its listing on Appendix I of the [[Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora]] (CITES).\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nEnglish physician, ornithologist, and artist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] first described the hyacinth macaw in 1790 under the [[binomial name]] ''Psittacus hyacinthinus'' based on a taxidermic specimen sent to England.<ref>{{cite book| last= Latham| first= John | year=1790 | title= Index Ornithologicus, Sive Systema Ornithologiae: Complectens Avium Divisionem in Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, Ipsarumque Varietates (Volume 1) | language=Latin | place=London | publisher = Leigh & Sotheby | page=84 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QV5UAAAAcAAJ&pg=PT107}}</ref> It is one of two extant and one probably extinct species of the South American macaw genus ''[[Anodorhynchus]]''.\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Hyacinth Macaw head.jpg|205px|thumb|left|Close-up of head]]\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus ZOO Dvur Kralove.jpg|right|thumb|205px|A skeleton exhibited at [[Dv\u016fr Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9 Zoo]] in [[Dv\u016fr Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9 nad Labem]], Czech Republic]]\nThe largest parrot by length in the world, the hyacinth macaw is {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long from the tip of its tail to the top of its head and weighs {{convert|1.2|\u2013|1.7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 70.\">Forshaw (2006). plate 70.</ref><ref name=\"animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu\">Hagan, E. (2004). [http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Anodorhynchus_hyacinthinus.html ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'']. Animal Diversity Web</ref> Each wing is {{convert|38.8|-|42.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 70.\" /> The tail is long and pointed.<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 70.\" /> Its feathers are entirely blue, lighter above. However, the neck feathers can sometimes be slightly grey. The ring around the parrots eyes and area just underneath the beak are a strong, vibrant yellow.\n\n== Behaviour ==\n\n=== Food and feeding ===\n[[File:Hyacinth macaw (Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus) head.JPG|thumb|upright|231px|A hyacinth macaw eating nut at [[Pantanal]] in Brazil]]\nThe majority of the hyacinth macaw diet is Brazil nuts, from native palms, such as acuri and bocaiuva palms.<ref name=\"WWF\">{{cite web|title=Hyacinth Macaw| url=http://www.wwf.org.br/english/informa/sitearara_arara.htm|publisher=[[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021104224234/http://www.wwf.org.br/english/informa/sitearara_arara.htm |archivedate=2002-11-04 |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref> They have very strong beaks for eating the kernels of hard [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] and seeds. Their strong beaks are even able to crack [[coconut]]s, the large [[brazil nut]] pods, and [[macadamia nut]]s. The birds also boast dry, smooth tongues with a bone inside them that makes them an effective tool for tapping into fruits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Macaw ''Psittacidae'' | url=http://animals.nationalgeographic.com/animals/birds/macaw/| publisher=National Geographic | accessdate=24 October 2013| date=2010-11-11}}</ref> The [[acuri]] nut is so hard, the parrots cannot feed on it until it has passed through the digestive system of cattle.<ref name=\"WWF\" /> In addition, they eat [[fruit]]s and other vegetable matter. The hyacinth macaw generally eats fruits, nuts, nectar, and various kinds of seeds. Also, they travel for the ripest of foods over a vast area.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Real Macaw Endangered Tropical Jewels | url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/nature/episodes/the-real-macaw/endangered-tropical-jewels/2734/ | publisher=Public Broadcasting Service | date=26 February 2004 | accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Pantanal]], hyacinth macaws feed almost exclusively on the nuts of ''[[Acrocomia aculeata]]'' and ''[[Attalea phalerata]]'' palm trees. This behaviour was recorded by the English [[natural history|naturalist]] [[Henry Walter Bates]] in his 1863 book ''[[The Naturalist on the River Amazons]]'', where he wrote that\n\n{{quote|It flies in pairs, and feeds on the hard nuts of several palms, but especially of the Mucuja (''[[Acrocomia aculeata|Acrocomia lasiospatha]]''). These nuts, which are so hard as to be difficult to break with a heavy hammer, are crushed to a pulp by the powerful beak of this macaw.|Bates<ref>{{ cite book | last=Bates | first=Henry Walter | author-link=Henry Walter Bates | year=1863 | title=The naturalist on the River Amazons, Volume 1 | volume=1 | publisher=John Murray | place=London | page=133 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/18557093}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Charles Darwin]] remarked on Bates's account of the species, calling it a \"splendid bird\" with its \"enormous beak\" able to feed on these palm nuts.<ref name=DarwinApp>{{cite web | url=http://www.lepidopterology.com/almanac/display.php?q=bates-amazon | title=An Appreciation: The Naturalist on the River Amazons by Henry Walter Bates | publisher=Natural History Review, vol iii | year=1863 | accessdate=27 March 2013 | author=Darwin, Charles | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607200303/http://www.lepidopterology.com/almanac/display.php?q=bates-amazon | archive-date=7 June 2011 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Tool use ===\nLimited tool use has been observed in both wild and captive hyacinth macaws. Reported sightings of tool use in wild parrots go as far back as 1863. Examples of tool use that have been observed usually involve a chewed leaf or pieces of wood. Macaws often incorporate these items when feeding on harder nuts. Their use allows the nuts the macaws eat to remain in position (prevent slipping) while they gnaw into it. It is not known whether this is learned social behavior or an innate trait, but observation on captive macaws shows that hand-raised macaws exhibit this behavior, as well. Comparisons show that older macaws were able to open seeds more efficiently.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1007/s10071-004-0221-3|pmid=15248094|title=Preliminary observations of tool use in captive hyacinth macaws (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'')|journal=Animal Cognition|volume=8|issue=1|pages=48\u201352|year=2004|last1=Borsari|first1=Andressa|last2=Ottoni|first2=Eduardo B.}}</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -Mato Grosso do Sul, Brazil -nest-8 (3).jpg|right|thumb|A pair in their nest]]\nNesting takes place between July and December, with nests constructed in tree cavities or cliff faces depending on the habitat.<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> In the Pantanal region, 90% of nests are constructed in the manduvi tree (''[[Sterculia apetala]]''). The hyacinth macaw depends on the [[toucan]], for its livelihood. The toucan contributes largely to seed dispersal of the manduvi tree that the macaw needs for reproduction.<ref name=Pizo08>{{cite journal|last1=Pizo|first1=Marco A.|first2=Camila I. |last2= Donatti|first3=Neiva R. |last3= Guedes|first4=Mauro |last4=Galetti|title=Conservation Puzzle: Endangered Hyacinth Macaw Depends on Its Nest Predator for Reproduction|journal=Biological Conservation |url=http://web.me.com/galetti/Labic/Publications_files/Pizo_Donatti_Galetti_BiolConserv2008_Conservartion%20puzzle%20endangered%20macaw%20depends%20on%20its%20nest%20predator%20for%20reproduction.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2007.12.023|volume=141|issue=3| year=2008|pages= 792\u201396|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref> However, the toucan is responsible for dispersing 83% of the seeds of ''Sterculia apetala'', but also consumes 53% of eggs preyed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hyacinth Macaw Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus| url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=1543|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref> Hollows of sufficient size are only found in trees around 60 years of age or older, and competition is fierce.<ref name= Pizo08 /> Existing holes are enlarged and then partially filled with wood chips.<ref name=\"MB WWF\">{{cite web| url= http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/conservation/species_programme/species_news/species_news_archive.cfm?12641/The-hyacinth-macaw-makes-a-comeback |first=Meindert |last=Brouwer|title=The hyacinth macaw makes a comeback |publisher=WWF|accessdate=20 July 2011 |date=21 April 2004}}</ref> The clutch size is one or two [[Egg (biology)|eggs]],<ref name=\"WWF\" /> although usually only one fledgling survives<ref name=\"WWF\" /> as the second egg hatches several days after the first, and the smaller fledgling cannot compete with the firstborn for food. A possible explanation for this behavior is what is called the insurance hypothesis. The macaw lays more eggs than can be normally fledged to compensate for earlier eggs that failed to hatch or firstborn chicks that did not survive.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kuniy|first= A.|title=Handling technique to increase the hyacinth macaw population (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') (Lalham, 1720) \u2013 Report of an experience in Pantanal, Brazil|pmid=16710531|doi=10.1590/S1519-69842006000200021 |journal=Brazilian Journal of Biology|volume= 66|issue= 1B| year= 2006| pages=381\u201382}}</ref> The incubation period lasts about a month, and the male tends to his mate whilst she incubates the eggs.<ref name=\"WWF\" /> The chicks leave the nest, or fledge, around 110 days of age,<ref name=\"Allgayer2009\" /> and remain dependent on their parents until six months of age.<ref name=\"WWF\" /> They are mature and begin breeding at seven years of age.\n\n=== General traits ===\nHyacinth macaws are the largest psittacine. They are also very even-tempered and can be calmer than other macaws, being known as \"gentle giants\".<ref name=\"Kalhagen\">{{cite web|last=Kalhagen|first=Alyson|title=Hyacinth Macaws|url=http://birds.about.com/od/breedsofbirds/p/hyacinths.htm| work=Pet Birds | publisher=About.com|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> An attending veterinarian must be aware of specific nutritional needs and pharmacologic sensitivities when dealing with them. Possibly due to genetic factors or captive rearing limitations, this species can become neurotic/phobic, which is problematic.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lennox|first=Angela| pages=35 | chapterurl=http://old.trustedpartner.com/docs/library/000087/02companion.pdf|title=Clinical Avian Medicine, Volume 1 |chapter=The companion bird}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus wild.jpg|thumb|left|Hyacinth macaws in their natural [[habitat]], the [[Pantanal]], Brazil]]\nThe hyacinth macaw survives today in three main populations in [[South America]]: In the [[Pantanal]] region of [[Brazil]], and adjacent eastern [[Bolivia]] and northeastern [[Paraguay]], in the [[Cerrado]] region of the eastern interior of Brazil ([[Maranh\u00e3o]], [[Piau\u00ed]], [[Bahia]], [[Tocantins]], [[Goi\u00e1s]], [[Mato Grosso]], [[Mato Grosso do Sul]], and [[Minas Gerais]]), and in the relatively open areas associated with the [[Tocantins River]], [[Xingu River]], [[Tapaj\u00f3s River]], and the [[Maraj\u00f3]] island in the eastern [[Amazon Basin]] of Brazil. Smaller, fragmented populations may occur in other areas. It prefers [[Arecaceae|palm]] [[swamp]]s, woodlands, and other semiopen, wooded habitats. It usually avoids dense, humid forest, and in regions dominated by such habitats, it is generally restricted to the edge or relatively open sections (e.g. along major rivers). In different areas of their range, these parrots are found in savannah grasslands, in dry thorn forest known as [[caatinga]], and in palm stands,<ref name=\"Birdlife\">{{cite web |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=1543 |title=Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''): BirdLife species factsheet |publisher=[[BirdLife International]] |accessdate=19 September 2013}} \u2013 via [[ARKive]]</ref> particularly the [[Moriche Palm]] (''Mauritia flexuosa'').<ref name=\"Forshaw (2006). plate 95.\">Forshaw (2006). page 95.</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\nThe hyacinth macaw has escaped or been deliberately released in to [[Florida]], USA, but there is no evidence that the population is breeding and may only persist due to continuing releases or escapes.[http://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/nonnatives/birds/hyacinth-macaw/]\n\n== Conservation and threats ==\n[[File:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -zoo de La Palmyre-8a.jpg|thumb|Captive macaw at [[La Palmyre Zoo]], [[France]]]]\nThe hyacinth macaw is an endangered species due to the cage bird trade and [[habitat loss]].<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> In the 1980s, an estimated 10,000 birds were taken from the wild and at least 50% were destined for the Brazilian market.<ref name=Mittermeier>{{cite web|title=Hyacinth Macaw Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=1543|accessdate=25 October 2013|year=1990|website=birdlife.org}}</ref> Throughout the macaw's range, habitat is being lost or altered due to the introduction of cattle ranching and mechanised agriculture, and the development of hydroelectric schemes.<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> Annual grass fires set by farmers can destroy nest trees, and regions previously inhabited by this macaw are now unsuitable also due to [[agriculture]] and plantations. Locally, it has been hunted for food, and the [[Kayapo]] Indians of Gorotire in south-central Brazil use its [[feather]]s to make headdresses and other ornaments. While overall greatly reduced in numbers, it remains locally common in the Brazilian Pantanal, where many ranch-owners now protect the macaws on their land.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.arkive.org/hyacinth-macaw/anodorhynchus-hyacinthinus/| title= Hyacinth macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'')| website= arkive.org| accessdate= 11 August 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150905060327/http://www.arkive.org/hyacinth-macaw/anodorhynchus-hyacinthinus/| archive-date= 5 September 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe hyacinth macaw is protected by law in Brazil and Bolivia,<ref name=\"Birdlife\" /> and commercial export is banned by its listing on Appendix I of the [[Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species|CITES]].<ref name=\"CITES\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cites.org/eng/app/ |title=The CITES Appendices |publisher=[[CITES]] |accessdate=19 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055732/http://www.cites.org/eng/app/ |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A number of long-term studies and conservation initiatives are in place; the Hyacinth Macaw Project in the Brazilian state of Mato Grosso do Sul has carried out important research by ringing individual birds, and has created a number of artificial nests to compensate for the small number of sites available in the region.<ref name=\"WWF\" />\n\nThe [[Minnesota Zoo]] with BioBrasil and the [[World Wildlife Fund]] are involved in hyacinth macaw conservation.<ref name=\"MB WWF\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnzoo.com/conservation/conservation_world_hyMacaw.asp|title= BioBrasil and the Minnesota Zoo working to save Hyacinth Macaws|publisher=Minnesota Zoo |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Causes of endangerment ===\nParrots as a whole, being of the family [[Psittacidae]], are some of the most threatened birds in the world. This family has the most endangered species of all bird families, especially in the [[neotropics]], the natural home of the hyacinth macaw, where 46 of 145 species are at a serious risk of global extinction.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Nest Poaching in Neotropical Parrots|journal=Conservation Biology |volume = 15 | issue = 3|pages=710\u2013720 | date = June 2001 | first1 = Timothy F. | last1 = Wright | first2 = Catherine A. | last2 = Toft | first3 = Ernesto | last3 = Enkerlin-Hoeflich | first4 = Jaime | last4 = Gonzalez-Elizondo | first5 = Mariana | last5 = Albornoz | first6 = Adriana | last6 = Rodr\u00edguez-Ferraro | first7 = Franklin | last7 = Rojas-Su\u00e1rez | first8 = Virginia | last8 = Sanz | first9 = Ana | last9 = Trujillo | first10 = Steven R. | last10 = Biessinger | first11 = Vincente | last11 = Berovidas A. |url = https://nature.berkeley.edu/beislab/BeissingerLab/publications/Wright_etal_2001_ConsBio.pdf |doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.2001.015003710.x}}</ref> This species qualifies as 'Vulnerable' on the [[IUCN Red List]] because the population has suffered rapid reductions with the remaining threats of illegal trapping for the cage bird trade and habitat loss <ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\">[http://eol.org/pages/1177958/overview ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'': Hyacinth Macaw]. 2013. [[Encyclopedia of Life]].</ref> A few serious threats to the survival of the species in the Pantanal include human activities, mainly those resulting in habitat loss, the burning of land for pasture maintenance, and illegal trapping <ref>{{cite journal|author=Pinho, J. B.|author2=Nogueira, Flavia M. B.|last-author-amp=yes |year=2003|title=Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') reproduction in the northern Pantanal, Mato Grosso, Brazil|url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/119497|journal= Ornitologia Neotropical |volume=14|pages= 29\u201338}}</ref> The exceptionally noisy, fearless, curious, sedentary, and predictable nature of this species, along with its specialization to only one or two species of palm in each part of its range, makes them especially vulnerable to capture, shooting, and [[habitat destruction]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|author=Collar, N. J.|author2=Juniper, A. T.|last-author-amp=yes |title= Dimensions and Causes of the Parrot Conservation Crisis|url=http://people.ds.cam.ac.uk/cns26/njc/Papers/Parrot%20crisis.PDF|publisher= International Council for Bird Preservation |pages=1\u20136, 9, 12\u201315, 19}}</ref> Eggs are also regularly preyed on by [[corvid]]s, [[opossum]]s, and [[coati]]s.<ref>[http://news.mongabay.com/2008/0313-hance_macaws.html Predator of the world's largest macaw key to its survival] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604144418/http://news.mongabay.com/2008/0313-hance_macaws.html |date=4 June 2009 }}. news.mongabay.com (2008-03-13)</ref> Adults have no known natural predators.<ref name=\"animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu\" /> The young are parasitized by larvae of flies of the genus ''[[Philornis]]''.<ref name=\"Allgayer2009\">{{cite journal|author=Allgayer, M. C.|author2=Guedes, N. M. R.|author3=Chiminazzo, C.|author4=Cziulik, M.|author5=Weimer, T. A. |year=2009|title=Clinical Pathology and Parasitologic Evaluation of Free Living Nestlings of the Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'')|journal=Journal of Wildlife Diseases|volume=45|issue=4|pages=972\u201381|pmid=19901373 |doi=10.7589/0090-3558-45.4.972}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the species has a low genetic variability, it does not necessarily pose a threat to their survival. This genetic structure accentuates the need for protection of hyacinth macaws from different regions to maintain their genetic diversity. Nevertheless, the most important factors negatively affecting the wild population prove to be [[habitat destruction]] and nest poaching.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1007/s10531-007-9312-1|year= 2008|title=Genetic variation and population structure of the endangered Hyacinth Macaw (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus''): implications for conservation|journal= Biodiversity and Conservation|volume= 17|issue= 4|pages= 765|last1= Faria|first1= Patr\u00edcia J.|last2= Guedes|first2= Neiva M. R.|last3= Yamashita|first3= Carlos|last4= Martuscelli|first4= Paulo|last5= Miyaki|first5= Cristina Y.}}</ref>\n\nIn the Pantanal, habitat loss is largely contributed to the creations of pastures for cattle, while in many other regions, it is the result of clearing land for colonization.<ref name=\"Tania F. R 2006\">{{cite journal|author=Tania F. R|author2=Glaucia H. F. R.|author3=Nevia M. R. G.|author4=Aramis A. G. |title= ''Chlamydophila psittaci'' in free-living Blue-fronted Amazon parrots (''Amazona aestiva'') and Hyacinth macaws (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') in the Pantanal of Mato Grosso do Sul, Brazil|journal= Veterinary Microbiology|volume= 117|issue= 2\u20134|pages= 235\u201341|pmid=16893616|year= 2006|doi= 10.1016/j.vetmic.2006.06.025}}</ref> Similarly, large areas of habitat in Amazonia have been lost for cattle ranching and hydroelectric power schemes on the Tocantins and Xingu Rivers. Many young manduvi trees are then being grazed on by cattle or burnt by fire, and the Gerias is speedily being converted to land for mechanized agriculture, cattle ranching, and exotic tree plantations.<ref name=IUCN /> Annual grass fires set by farmers destroy a number of nest trees, and the rise of agriculture and plantations has made habitats formerly populated by the macaws unsuitable to maintain their livelihoods.<ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\" /> Moreover, increase in commercial demand for feather art by the Kayapo Indians threatens the species, as up to 10 macaws are needed to make a single headdress.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nIn the event of the macaws being taken from their natural environment, a variety of factors alter their health such as inadequate hygiene conditions, feeding, and overpopulation during the illegal practice of pet trade. Once birds are captured and brought into captivity, their mortality rates can become very high.<ref name=\"Tania F. R 2006\" /> Records reveal a Paraguayan dealer receiving 300 unfeathered young in 1972, with all but three not surviving. Due to the poor survival rates of the young, poachers concentrate more heavily on adult birds, which depletes the population at a rapid pace.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nAccording to Article 111 of Bolivian Environmental Law #1333, all persons involved in the trade, capture, and transportation without authorization of wild animals will suffer a two-year prison sentence, along with a fine equivalent to 100% of the value of the animal.<ref name=\"Luecker, H. 2000\">{{cite journal|author=L\u00fccker, H.|author2=Patzwahl, S.|last-author-amp=yes |title= The European Endangered Species Programme (EEP) for the Hyacinth macaw ''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'' from 1989 to 1998|journal= International Zoo Yearbook|volume= 37|pages= 178\u2013183|doi=10.1111/j.1748-1090.2000.tb00720.x|year= 2000}}</ref> While many trackers have been arrested, the illegal pet trade still largely continues in Santa Cruz, Bolivia. Unfortunately, animal trafficking is not necessarily viewed as a priority in the city, leaving national departmental and municipal governments unwilling to halt the trade in city centers, and local police reluctant to get involved. This ideology has in turn resulted in a lack of enforcement regarding trade in both CITES-restricted species and threatened species, with little to no restrictions regarding humane treatment of the animals, disease control, or proper hygiene. In the trade centers, the hyacinth macaw demanded the highest price of US$1,000, proving it to be a very desirable and valued bird in the pet trade industry.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Mauricio, H.|author2=Hennessey, B.|last-author-amp=yes |title=Quantifying the illegal parrot trade in Santa Cruz de la Sierra, Bolivia, with emphasis on threatened species|journal=Bird Conservation International|volume=17|issue=4|pages=295\u2013300|doi=10.1017/S0959270907000858 |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservation steps taken to preserve the hyacinth macaw ===\n\nIn 1989, the [[European Endangered Species Programme]] for the hyacinth macaw was founded as a result of concerns about the status of the wild population and the lack of successful breeding in captivity.<ref name=\"Luecker, H. 2000\" /> Breeding in captivity still remains difficult, being that hand-reared hyacinth macaw offspring have demonstrated to have higher mortality rates, especially within the first month of life. Additionally, they have a higher incidence of acute crop stasis than other macaw species due, in part, to their specific dietary requirements.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Casares, M.|author2=F. Enders|year= 1998|title= Experiences in the hand-rearing of hyacinth macaws (''Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus'') in Loro Parque|journal= Zoologische Garten |volume=68|pages= 65\u201374}}</ref> The hyacinth macaw is protected by law in Brazil and Bolivia, and international trade is prohibited by its listing on Appendix I of the CITES.<ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\" /> Appendix I has banned exporting the bird in all countries of origin, and several studies and conservational initiatives have been taken.<ref name=IUCN /> The Hyacinth Macaw Project in the Caiman Ecological Refuge, located in the Pantanal, has employed artificial nests and chick management techniques, along with effectively raising awareness among cattle ranchers. Many ranch owners in the Pantanal and Gerais, to protect the birds, no longer allow trappers on their properties.<ref name=IUCN />\n\nA number of conservation actions have been proposed, including the study of the current range, population status, and extent of trading in different parts of its range. Additionally, propositions have been made to assess the effectiveness of artificial nest boxes, enforce legal measures preventing trade, and experiment with ecotourism at one or two sites to encourage donors.<ref name=IUCN /> Furthermore, the Hyacinth Macaw Project in Mato Grosso do Sul has carried out important research by ringing individual birds and has created a number of artificial nests to compensate for the small number of sites available in the region.<ref name=\"Hyacinth Macaw 2013\" /> Furthermore, proposals to list the species as Endangered under the U.S. Endangered Species Act have been made to further protective measures in the US and to create Bolivian and Paraguayan trade management authorities under presidential control.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n=== Long-term prospects ===\nEach of the three main populations should be managed as a separate biological entity so as to avoid numbers dropping below 500. While the birds may be in decline in the wild, notably higher populations of captive macaws are being held in zoos and private collections. If success in managing and replanting the macaw's food trees and erecting nest boxes as an experiment in the Pantanals is seen, the species could survive. Survival rates could also be enhanced if ranch owners would leave all large and potential nest trees standing and eliminate all trapping on their properties. Ultimately, should these factors work in tandem with erection of nest boxes, fencing off of certain saplings, and the planting of others, the long-term prospects of the hyacinth macaw species would be greatly improved.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"130px\">\nHyacinth macaws (Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus) 2.jpg\nHyacinth macaw (Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus) in flight.JPG\nFile:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -pet parrot-8a.jpg|Pet hyacinth macaw on arm\nFile:Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus -pet on bike handlebars-8.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of macaws]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n* {{Cite book |first=Joseph M. |last=Forshaw |authorlink=Joseph Forshaw |title=Parrots of the World; an Identification Guide |others=Illustrated by [[Frank Knight (artist)|Frank Knight]] |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |isbn=978-0-691-09251-5 |nopp=yes |year=2006 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/parrotsofworldid0000fors }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Anodorhynchus hyacinthinus}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/hyacinth-macaw-anodorhynchus-hyacinthinus Hyacinth macaw] on the Internet Bird Collection\n* {{ARKive}}\n* [http://www.bluemacaws.org/ The Blue Macaws website]\n* [http://www.macaw-facts.com/species/blue-macaw-hyacinth-macaw-hyacinthine-macaw/ In-Depth Blue Macaw Research]\n* [http://www.freesound.org/samplesViewSingle.php?id=56513 Audio File of the hyacinth macaw]\n\n{{Macaws}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q463154}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:macaw, hyacinth}}\n[[Category:Anodorhynchus|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Macaws|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Talking birds]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Cerrado]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Pantanal]]\n[[Category:Birds of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|hyacinth macaw]]\n[[Category:Species endangered by habitat loss]]\n[[Category:Species endangered by the pet trade]]\n", "name_user": "Simabkhani", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReproduction)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyacinth_macaw"}
{"title_page": "Bayou Fourche order of battle", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{multiple image|caption_align=left|header_align=center|footer_align=center|align=right\n|image1=Frederick Steele cropped.jpg |caption1=Maj. Gen. Frederick Steele, USA |width1=200 |height1=150\n|alt1=Black and white photo shows a heavily-bearded man staring directly into the camera. He wears a dark, double-breasted military uniform with general's stars on the shoulder tabs.    \n|image2=Sterling Price.jpg |caption2=Maj. Gen. Sterling Price, CSA |width2=200 |height2=150\n|alt2=Black and white print shows a clean-shaven man wearing a gray double-breasted military uniform with three general's stars on the collar. \n|footer=The battle pitted Steele's Union troops against Price's Confederates.}}\nThe '''[[Battle of Bayou Fourche]]''' (September 10, 1863) saw [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces under the overall command of [[Frederick Steele]] clash with Confederate forces led by [[Sterling Price]] near [[Little Rock, Arkansas]]. Steele's cavalry commanded by [[John Davidson (general)|John W. Davidson]] crossed to the south side of the [[Arkansas River]] and compelled the Confederate cavalry under [[John S. Marmaduke]] to abandon its defensive position behind [[Fourche Creek (Arkansas)|Bayou Fourche]]. Price's outnumbered forces evacuated Little Rock and withdrew south to [[Arkadelphia, Arkansas|Arkadelphia]]. The Union occupation of Little Rock was the final action in a campaign that started on August 18 when Steele's troops marched west from [[DeValls Bluff, Arkansas|DeValls Bluff]].{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=457}}\n\n==Abbreviations used==\n===Military rank===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* '''Maj. Gen.''' = [[Major General]]\n* '''Brig. Gen.''' = [[Brigadier General]]\n* '''Col.''' = [[Colonel]]\n* '''Lieut. Col.''' = [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n* '''Maj.''' = [[Major]]\n* '''Capt.''' = [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]\n* '''1st Lieut.''' = [[First Lieutenant]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* '''(k)''' = [[killed in action]]\n* '''(w)''' = [[Wounded in action|wounded]]\n* '''(c)''' = captured\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Artillery===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* '''10lb PR'''  = [[10-pounder Parrott rifle]]\n* '''12lb How'''  = [[M1841 12-pounder howitzer]]\n* '''3-in OR'''   = [[3-inch Ordnance rifle]]\n* '''3.8-in JR''' = [[3.8-inch James rifle]]\n* '''6lb Gun'''   = [[M1841 6-pounder field gun]]\n* '''6lb Rifle''' = M1841 6-pounder field gun (rifled)\n* '''Mtn How'''   = [[M1841 mountain howitzer]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Union forces==\nUnion Army: Maj. Gen. [[Frederick Steele]]{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n*Present aggregate (Aug. 18, 1863): 13,000, 57 guns (18 guns with Davidson), 14,500 including True's brigade.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=457}} \n*Present for duty (Sept. 10, 1863): 10,477{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n*Present aggregate (Aug. 18, 1863): 13,207, 49 guns{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|p=207}}\n*Present for duty (Aug. 18, 1863): 4,652 cavalry, 4,493 infantry, 288 artillery, 9,433 total{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|p=207}}\n*Casualties: 18 killed, 118 wounded, 1 missing{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n*Cavalry Escort:{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}} \n**Company D, [[3rd Illinois Cavalry Regiment]], 1st Lieut. James K. McLean\n**[[Independent Illinois Volunteer Cavalry Companies|Kane County, Illinois Cavalry]], 1st Lieut. Eben C. Litherland  \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:75%;\"\n|+Union Army: Little Rock Expedition{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n! width=15% | Division\n! width=15% | Brigade\n! width=30% | Unit\n! width=15% | Commander\n|-\n| rowspan=14 | '''First (Cavalry) Division'''<br>Brig. Gen. [[John Davidson (general)|John W. Davidson]]<br>6,000 cavalry and 18 guns<br>[[File:John W Davidson.jpg|thumb|center|upright=0.4|Davidson]]\n| rowspan=3 | First Brigade<br>Col. [[Lewis Merrill]]\n