}}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, 3rd Quarter 1863, Iowa's Batteries |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2018a |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/2018/05/29/sum-stmt-3qtr63-iowa/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, 3rd Quarter 1863, Ohio Independent Batteries, Part 1 |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2018b |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/2018/10/29/sum-stmt-3qtr63-oh-ind-p1/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, 3rd Quarter 1863, Ohio Independent Batteries, Part 2 |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2018c |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/2018/10/31/sum-stmt-3qtr63-oh-ind-p2/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, 4th Quarter 1863, 1st Missouri Artillery |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2019a |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/2019/08/19/sum-stmt-4qtr63-mo-1/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, 4th Quarter 1863, 2nd Missouri Artillery |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2019b |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/tag/battery-m-2nd-missouri-artillery/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, December 31 1862, Independent Illinois Batteries and \"Others\" |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2015 |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/tag/vaughns-independent-illinois-battery/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref={{harvid|Official Records|1888}} |publisher=United States War Dept. |title=The War of the Rebellion: A Compilation of the Official Records of the Union And Confederate Armies. Series 1, Volume 22, In Two Parts. Part 1, Reports |volume=22 |year=1888 |url=http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth154600/m1/471/?q=Etter |access-date=July 26, 2013 |publication-place=University of North Texas Libraries, The Portal to Texas History }}\n\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American Civil War orders of battle]]\n[[Category:Battle of Bayou Fourche]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{multiple image|caption_align=left|header_align=center|footer_align=center|align=right\n|image1=Frederick Steele cropped.jpg |caption1=Maj. Gen. Frederick Steele, USA |width1=200 |height1=150\n|alt1=Black and white photo shows a heavily-bearded man staring directly into the camera. He wears a dark, double-breasted military uniform with general's stars on the shoulder tabs.    \n|image2=Sterling Price.jpg |caption2=Maj. Gen. Sterling Price, CSA |width2=200 |height2=150\n|alt2=Black and white print shows a clean-shaven man wearing a gray double-breasted military uniform with three general's stars on the collar. \n|footer=The battle pitted Steele's Union troops against Price's Confederates.}}\nThe '''[[Battle of Bayou Fourche]]''' (September 10, 1863) saw [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces under the overall command of [[Frederick Steele]] clash with Confederate forces led by [[Sterling Price]] near [[Little Rock, Arkansas]]. Steele's cavalry commanded by [[John Davidson (general)|John W. Davidson]] crossed to the south side of the [[Arkansas River]] and compelled the Confederate cavalry under [[John S. Marmaduke]] to abandon its defensive position behind [[Fourche Creek (Arkansas)|Bayou Fourche]]. Price's outnumbered forces evacuated Little Rock and withdrew south to [[Arkadelphia, Arkansas|Arkadelphia]]. The Union occupation of Little Rock was the final action in a campaign that started on August 18 when Steele's troops marched west from [[DeValls Bluff, Arkansas|DeValls Bluff]].{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=457}}\n\n==Abbreviations used==\n===Military rank===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* '''Maj. Gen.''' = [[Major General]]\n* '''Brig. Gen.''' = [[Brigadier General]]\n* '''Col.''' = [[Colonel]]\n* '''Lieut. Col.''' = [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n* '''Maj.''' = [[Major]]\n* '''Capt.''' = [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]\n* '''1st Lieut.''' = [[First Lieutenant]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* '''(k)''' = [[killed in action]]\n* '''(w)''' = [[Wounded in action|wounded]]\n* '''(c)''' = captured\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Artillery===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* '''10lb PR'''  = [[10-pounder Parrott rifle]]\n* '''12lb How'''  = [[M1841 12-pounder howitzer]]\n* '''3-in OR'''   = [[3-inch Ordnance rifle]]\n* '''3.8-in JR''' = [[3.8-inch James rifle]]\n* '''6lb Gun'''   = [[M1841 6-pounder field gun]]\n* '''6lb Rifle''' = M1841 6-pounder field gun (rifled)\n* '''Mtn How'''   = [[M1841 mountain howitzer]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Union forces==\nUnion Army: Maj. Gen. [[Frederick Steele]]{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n*Present aggregate (Aug. 18, 1863): 13,000, 57 guns (18 guns with Davidson), 14,500 including True's brigade.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=457}} \n*Present for duty (Sept. 10, 1863): 10,477{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n*Present aggregate (Aug. 18, 1863): 13,207, 49 guns{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|p=207}}\n*Present for duty (Aug. 18, 1863): 4,652 cavalry, 4,493 infantry, 288 artillery, 9,433 total{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|p=207}}\n*Casualties: 18 killed, 118 wounded, 1 missing{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n*Cavalry Escort:{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}} \n**Company D, [[3rd Illinois Cavalry Regiment]], 1st Lieut. James K. McLean\n**[[Independent Illinois Volunteer Cavalry Companies|Kane County, Illinois Cavalry]], 1st Lieut. Eben C. Litherland  \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:75%;\"\n|+Union Army: Little Rock Expedition{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n! width=15% | Division\n! width=15% | Brigade\n! width=30% | Unit\n! width=15% | Commander\n|-\n| rowspan=14 | '''First (Cavalry) Division'''<br>Brig. Gen. [[John Davidson (general)|John W. Davidson]]<br>6,000 cavalry and 18 guns<br>[[File:John W Davidson.jpg|thumb|center|upright=0.4|Davidson]]\n| rowspan=3 | First Brigade<br>Col. [[Lewis Merrill]]\n| [[2nd Missouri Volunteer Cavalry|2nd Missouri Volunteer Cavalry Regiment]] (Merrill's Horse) || Maj. Garrison Harker\n|-\n| 7th Missouri Volunteer Cavalry Regiment || Lieut. Col. John L. Chandler\n|-\n| [[8th Regiment Missouri Volunteer Cavalry|8th Missouri Volunteer Cavalry Regiment]] || Col. Washington F. Geiger\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | Second Brigade<br>Col. [[John Montgomery Glover]]\n| [[10th Illinois Cavalry Regiment]] || Col. Dudley Wickersham<br>Lieut. Col. James Stuart\n|-\n| [[1st Iowa Volunteer Cavalry Regiment]] || Lt. Col. Daniel Anderson<br>Maj. Joseph W. Caldwell\n|-\n| [[3rd Missouri Volunteer Cavalry|3d Missouri Volunteer Cavalry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. T. G. Black<br>Capt. J. H. Reed\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | Reserve Brigade<br>Col. John. F. Ritter\n| [[13th Illinois Cavalry Regiment]] || Maj. Lothar Lippert\n|-\n| [[3rd Iowa Volunteer Cavalry Regiment]] || Maj. George Duffield\n|-\n| [[1st Missouri Volunteer Cavalry Regiment]] || Capt. J. W. Fuller\n|-\n| [[32nd Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] (mounted) || Lieut. Col. Edward H. Mix<br>Maj. Gustavus A. Eberhard\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | Artillery<br>Capt. Julius L. Hadley\n| [[Battery K, 2nd Missouri Light Artillery]] (4 3-in OR, 2 12lb How){{sfn|Swain|2019b}}|| 1st Lieut. T. S. Clarkson\n|-\n| [[Battery M, 2nd Missouri Light Artillery]] (4 Mtn How){{sfn|Swain|2019b}} || Capt. Gustav Stange\n|-\n| Howitzer Battery, 2d Missouri Cavalry{{sfn|Official Records|1888}} || 1st Lieut. G. F. Lovejoy ('''w'''){{sfn|Official Records|1888}}\n|-\n| [[25th Ohio Battery]] (2 3-in OR, 4 6lb Rifle){{sfn|Swain|2018c}} || 1st Lieut. E. B. Hubbard\n|-\n| rowspan=11 | '''Second Division'''<br>Col. William E. McLean<br>Col. [[Adolph Englemann]]\n| rowspan=6 | First Brigade<br>Col. William H. Graves\n| [[18th Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Col. Daniel H. Brush\n|-\n| [[43rd Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Maj. Charles Stephani\n|-\n| [[54th Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Col. Greenville M. Mitchell\n|-\n| [[61st Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Simon P. Ohr\n|-\n| [[106th Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Henry Yates\n|-\n| [[12th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. [[Dwight May]]\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | Second Brigade<br>Col. [[Oliver Wood (general)|Oliver Wood]]\n| [[126th Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Ezra M. Beardsley\n|-\n| [[40th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Samuel F. Cooper\n|-\n| [[3rd Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Col. [[Christopher Columbus Andrews|Christopher C. Andrews]]\n|-\n| [[22nd Ohio Infantry|22nd Ohio Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Homer Thrall\n|-\n| [[27th Wisconsin Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Col. [[Conrad Krez]]\n|-\n| rowspan=6 | '''Third Division'''<br>Brig. Gen. [[Samuel Allen Rice]]<br>[[File:Samuelallenricecommons.jpg|thumb|center|upright=0.3|Rice]]\n| rowspan=3 | First Brigade<br>Col. Charles W. Kittredge\n| [[43rd Indiana Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. John C. Major\n|-\n| [[36th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Francis M. Drake\n|-\n| [[77th Ohio Infantry|77th Ohio Infantry Regiment]] || Col. William B. Mason\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | Second Brigade<br>Col. Thomas H. Benton Jr. \n| [[29th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Robert F. Patterson\n|-\n| [[33rd Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Cyrus H. Mackey\n|-\n| [[28th Wisconsin Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Maj. Calvert C. White\n|- \n| rowspan=2 | '''Independent Cavalry'''\n| rowspan=2 | Independent Brigade<br>Col. [[Powell Clayton]]\n| [[1st Indiana Cavalry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Thomas N. Pace\n|-\n| [[5th Kansas Volunteer Cavalry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Wilton A. Jenkins\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | '''Independent Infantry'''\n| rowspan=5 | Independent Brigade<br>Col. James M. True\n| [[49th Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Col. Phineas Pease\n|-\n| [[62nd Illinois Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Stephen M. Meeker\n|-\n| [[50th Indiana Infantry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. Samuel T. Wells\n|-\n| [[27th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] || Col. [[James Isham Gilbert]]\n|-\n| [[Springfield Illinois Independent Battery]] (6 3.8-in JR){{sfn|Swain|2015}} || Capt. Thomas F. Vaughn\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | '''Independent Artillery'''\n| rowspan=4 | Artillery Brigade<br>Capt. Mortimer M. Haden\n| [[3rd Iowa Independent Battery Light Artillery]]<br>(4 6lb Gun, 3 12lb How, 1 3-in OR, 1 10lb PR){{sfn|Swain|2018a}} || 1st Lieut. Melvil C. Wright\n|-\n| [[Battery K, 1st Missouri Light Artillery]] (4 10lb PR){{sfn|Swain|2019a}} || Capt. Stillman O. Fish\n|-\n| [[5th Ohio Battery]] (2 6lb Gun, 2 3.8-in JR){{sfn|Swain|2018b}} || 1st Lieut. John D. Burner\n|-\n| [[11th Ohio Battery]] (2 6lb Gun, 2 12lb How, 1 6lb Rifle){{sfn|Swain|2018b}} || Capt. Frank C. Sands\n|-\n|}\n\n==Confederate forces==\nConfederate Army: Maj. Gen. [[Sterling Price]]\n*On July 23, 1863, the department commander Lieut. Gen. [[Theophilus H. Holmes]] became ill and was superseded by Price.{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|p=208}}  \n*On September 6, 1863, Brig. Gen. Marmaduke mortally wounded Brig. Gen. Walker in a duel. Col. Dobbins assumed command of Walker's division.{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|pp=220\u2013221}} \n*Marmaduke placed Dobbins under arrest on September 10 for disobedience of orders and command devolved upon Col. Newton. Price later suspended Dobbins's arrest.{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|pp=221\u2013222}}\n*Present for duty: 7,749. About 6,500 were north of the Arkansas River and 1,250 south of the river.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=457}}\n*Aggregate present (September): 10,665, 32 guns. Present for duty: 8,532.{{sfn|Dimitry|Harrell|1899|p=207}}\n*Casualties: 12 killed, 34 wounded, 18 missing.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:75%;\"\n|+Confederate Army: Little Rock Expedition{{sfn|Official Records|1888}}{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987|p=461}}\n! width=15% | Division\n! width=15% | Brigade\n! width=30% | Unit\n! width=15% | Commander\n|-\n| rowspan=9 | '''Marmaduke's Cavalry Division'''<br>Brig. Gen. [[John S. Marmaduke]]<br>[[File:General John S. Marmaduke, C.S.A. (9241066570).jpg|thumb|center|upright=0.3|Marmaduke]]\n| rowspan=4 | [[Shelby's Iron Brigade|Shelby's Brigade]]<br>Lieut. Col. [[Benjamin Franklin Gordon|Benjamin F. Gordon]]\n| [[5th Missouri Cavalry Regiment (Confederate)|5th Missouri Cavalry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. B. F. Gordon\n|-\n| [[6th Missouri Cavalry Regiment (Confederate)|6th Missouri Cavalry Regiment]] || Col. [[Gideon W. Thompson]]\n|-\n| [[10th Missouri Cavalry Battalion (Confederate)|10th Missouri Cavalry Battalion]] || Maj. Benjamin Elliott\n|-\n| [[2nd Missouri Field Battery (Confederate)|2nd Missouri Field Battery]] (2 6lb Gun, 2 10lb PR){{sfn|McGhee|2008|p=7}} || Capt. Joseph Bledsoe\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | Marmaduke's Brigade<br>Col. William L. Jeffers\n| [[8th Missouri Cavalry Regiment (Confederate)|8th Missouri Cavalry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. S. J. Ward\n|-\n| [[3rd Missouri Cavalry Regiment (Confederate)|3rd Missouri Cavalry Regiment]] || Maj. L. A. Campbell\n|-\n| [[4th Missouri Cavalry Regiment (Confederate)|4th Missouri Cavalry Regiment]] || Lieut. Col. W. J. Preston\n|-\n| [[11th Missouri Cavalry Battalion (Confederate)|11th Missouri Cavalry Battalion]] || Lieut. Col. M. L. Young\n|-\n| Prairie Gun Battery, Missouri Artillery || 1st Lieut. T. J. Williams\n|-\n| rowspan=8 | '''Walker's Cavalry Division'''<br>Brig. Gen. [[Lucius M. Walker]]<br>Col. [[Archibald S. Dobbins]]<br>Col. [[Robert C. Newton]]<br>[[File:LMWalker.jpg|thumb|center|upright=0.3|Walker]]\n| rowspan=3 | Dobbin's Brigade<br>Col. A. S. Dobbins<br>Col. R. C. Newton\n| [[1st Arkansas Cavalry Regiment (Dobbin's)]] || Maj. S. Corley ('''k''')<br>Capt. M. M. Bateman\n|-\n| [[5th Arkansas Cavalry Regiment]] || Col. R. C. Newton, Maj. J. P. Bull\n|-\n| [[6th 